</table>
<p><b>Groupe Renault</b> (<small>French:&#160;</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_French" title="Help:IPA for French">[ɡʁup ʁəˈno]</a></span>) is a French <a href="/wiki/Multinational_corporation" title="Multinational corporation">multinational</a> <a href="/wiki/Automotive_industry" title="Automotive industry">automobile manufacturer</a> established in 1899.<sup id="cite_ref-LAE_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LAE-8">[8]</a></sup> The company produces a range of cars and vans, and in the past has manufactured trucks, tractors, tanks, buses/coaches and <a href="/wiki/Autorail" title="Autorail">autorail</a> vehicles.</p>
<p>According to the <a href="/wiki/Organisation_Internationale_des_Constructeurs_d%27Automobiles" title="Organisation Internationale des Constructeurs d'Automobiles">Organisation Internationale des Constructeurs d'Automobiles</a>, in 2015 Renault was the <a href="/wiki/Automotive_industry" title="Automotive industry">tenth biggest automaker in the world</a> by production volume,<sup id="cite_ref-OICA2_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OICA2-9">[9]</a></sup> with 50.5% of sales coming outside of Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Renault%E2%80%93Nissan_Alliance" title="Renault–Nissan Alliance">Renault–Nissan Alliance</a> is the fourth-largest automotive group.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup></p>
<p>Headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Boulogne-Billancourt" title="Boulogne-Billancourt">Boulogne-Billancourt</a>, near <a href="/wiki/Paris" title="Paris">Paris</a>, the Renault group is made up of the namesake Renault marque and subsidiaries, <a href="/wiki/Automobile_Dacia" title="Automobile Dacia">Automobile Dacia</a> from Romania, and <a href="/wiki/Renault_Samsung_Motors" title="Renault Samsung Motors">Renault Samsung Motors</a> from South Korea.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> Renault has a 43.4% controlling stake in <a href="/wiki/Nissan" title="Nissan">Nissan</a> of Japan,<sup id="cite_ref-AUTONEWS_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AUTONEWS-13">[13]</a></sup> a 37% indirectly-owned stake in <a href="/wiki/AvtoVAZ" title="AvtoVAZ">AvtoVAZ</a> of Russia,<sup id="cite_ref-AUTONEWS2_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AUTONEWS2-14">[14]</a></sup> and a 1.55% stake in <a href="/wiki/Daimler_AG" title="Daimler AG">Daimler AG</a> of Germany (since 2012, Renault manufactures engines for the Daimler's Mercedes <a href="/wiki/Mercedes_Benz_A-Class" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes Benz A-Class">A-Class</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mercedes_Benz_B-Class" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes Benz B-Class">B-Class</a> cars<sup id="cite_ref-Parterships_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Parterships-15">[15]</a></sup>). Renault also owns subsidiaries RCI Banque (automotive financing), Renault Retail Group (automotive distribution) and Motrio (automotive parts). Renault has various joint ventures, including <a href="/wiki/Oyak-Renault" title="Oyak-Renault">Oyak-Renault</a> (Turkey), <a href="/wiki/Renault_Pars" title="Renault Pars">Renault Pars</a> (Iran). <a href="/wiki/Carlos_Ghosn" title="Carlos Ghosn">Carlos Ghosn</a> is the current chairman and CEO. The French government owns a 19.73% share of Renault as of April 2015.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Renault_Trucks" title="Renault Trucks">Renault Trucks</a>, previously known as Renault Véhicules Industriels, has been part of <a href="/wiki/Volvo_Trucks" title="Volvo Trucks">Volvo Trucks</a> since 2001. <a href="/wiki/Renault_Agriculture" title="Renault Agriculture">Renault Agriculture</a> became 100% owned by German agricultural equipment manufacturer <a href="/wiki/CLAAS" class="mw-redirect" title="CLAAS">CLAAS</a> in 2008.</p>
<p>Together Renault and Nissan are investing €4&#160;billion (US$5.16&#160;billion) in eight electric vehicles over three to four years beginning in 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> In 2013, new Renault vehicles had the lowest average <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">CO<sub>2</sub></a> emissions among generalist brands in Europe, with 110.1g/km.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault is known for its role in <a href="/wiki/Motor_sport" class="mw-redirect" title="Motor sport">motor sport</a>, particularly rallying, <a href="/wiki/Renault_F1" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault F1">Formula 1</a> and <a href="/wiki/DAMS#Formula_E" title="DAMS">Formula E</a>. Its early work on mathematical curve <a href="/wiki/3d_modeling" class="mw-redirect" title="3d modeling">modeling</a> for car bodies is important in the history of <a href="/wiki/Computer_graphics" title="Computer graphics">computer graphics</a>.</p>
<p></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Founding_and_early_years_.281898.E2.80.931918.29">Founding and early years (1898–1918)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Founding and early years (1898–1918)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg/220px-Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg" width="220" height="213" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg/330px-Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg/440px-Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg 2x" data-file-width="719" data-file-height="695" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Louis_Renault_with_his_first_car.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Louis_Renault_(industrialist)" title="Louis Renault (industrialist)">Louis Renault</a> in 1903</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The Renault corporation was founded in 1899 as <i>Société Renault Frères</i> by <a href="/wiki/Louis_Renault_(industrialist)" title="Louis Renault (industrialist)">Louis Renault</a> and his brothers <a href="/wiki/Marcel_Renault" title="Marcel Renault">Marcel</a> and <a href="/wiki/Fernand_Renault" title="Fernand Renault">Fernand</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-LAE_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LAE-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> Louis was a bright, aspiring young engineer who had already designed and built several prototypes before teaming up with his brothers, who had honed their business skills working for their father's <a href="/wiki/Textile" title="Textile">textile</a> firm. While Louis handled design and production, Marcel and Fernand managed the business.<sup id="cite_ref-AIM_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AIM-19">[19]</a></sup></p>
<p>The first Renault car, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Voiturette" title="Renault Voiturette">Renault Voiturette</a> 1CV, was sold to a friend of Louis' father after giving him a test ride on 24 December 1898.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg/220px-Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg" width="220" height="220" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg/330px-Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg/440px-Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="801" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Voiturette_1901.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
1901 Voiturette Renault Type D Série B</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Renault d'époque.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg/220px-Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg/330px-Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg/440px-Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3980" data-file-height="2657" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_d%27%C3%A9poque.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1903, Renault began to manufacture its own engines; until then it had purchased them from <a href="/wiki/De_Dion-Bouton" title="De Dion-Bouton">De Dion-Bouton</a>. The first major volume sale came in 1905 when Société des Automobiles de Place bought Renault AG1 cars to establish a fleet of <a href="/wiki/Taxi" class="mw-redirect" title="Taxi">taxis</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-TEMBEF_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TEMBEF-20">[20]</a></sup> These vehicles were later used by the French military to transport troops during <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a> which earned them the nickname "<a href="/wiki/Renault_Taxi_de_la_Marne" title="Renault Taxi de la Marne">Taxi de la Marne</a>."<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> By 1907, a significant percentage London and Paris taxis had been built by Renault.<sup id="cite_ref-TEMBEF_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TEMBEF-20">[20]</a></sup> Renault was also the best-selling foreign brand in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York</a> in 1907 and 1908.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> In 1908 the company produced 3,575 units, becoming the country's largest car manufacturer.<sup id="cite_ref-TEMBEF_20-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TEMBEF-20">[20]</a></sup></p>
<p>The brothers recognised the value of publicity that participation in <a href="/wiki/Motor_racing" class="mw-redirect" title="Motor racing">motor racing</a> could generate for their vehicles. Renault made itself known through succeeding in the first city-to-city races held in Switzerland, producing rapid sales growth. Both Louis and Marcel raced company vehicles, but Marcel was killed in an accident during the 1903 <a href="/wiki/Paris-Madrid_race" class="mw-redirect" title="Paris-Madrid race">Paris-Madrid race</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> Although Louis never raced again, his company remained very involved, including <a href="/wiki/Ferenc_Szisz" title="Ferenc Szisz">Ferenc Szisz</a> winning the first <a href="/wiki/Grand_Prix_motor_racing" title="Grand Prix motor racing">Grand Prix motor racing</a> event<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup> in a <a href="/wiki/Renault_Grand_Prix" title="Renault Grand Prix">Renault AK 90CV</a> <a href="/wiki/1906_French_Grand_Prix" title="1906 French Grand Prix">in 1906</a>.</p>
<p>Louis took full control of the company as the only remaining brother in 1906 when Fernand retired for health reasons.<sup id="cite_ref-AIM_19-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AIM-19">[19]</a></sup> Fernand died in 1909 and Louis became the sole owner, renaming the company <i>Société des Automobiles Renault</i> (Renault Automobile Company).<sup id="cite_ref-LAE_8-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LAE-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-TEMBEF_20-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TEMBEF-20">[20]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault fostered its reputation for innovation from very early on. At the time, cars were luxury items. The price of the smallest Renaults at the time were ₣3000 <a href="/wiki/Franc" title="Franc">francs</a>; an amount equal to ten years pay for the average worker. In 1905 the company introduced mass-production techniques and <a href="/wiki/Taylorism" class="mw-redirect" title="Taylorism">Taylorism</a> in 1913.<sup id="cite_ref-ROH_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ROH-25">[25]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault manufactured <a href="/wiki/Buses" class="mw-redirect" title="Buses">buses</a> and commercial cargo vehicles in the pre-war years. The first real <a href="/wiki/Commercial_truck" class="mw-redirect" title="Commercial truck">commercial truck</a> from the company was introduced in 1906.<sup id="cite_ref-TT_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TT-26">[26]</a></sup> During World War I, it branched out into <a href="/wiki/Ammunition" title="Ammunition">ammunition</a>, military <a href="/wiki/Aircraft_engine" title="Aircraft engine">aircraft engines</a><sup id="cite_ref-TEMBEF_20-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TEMBEF-20">[20]</a></sup> (the first <a href="/wiki/Rolls-Royce_Limited" title="Rolls-Royce Limited">Rolls-Royce</a> <a href="/wiki/Aircraft_engines" class="mw-redirect" title="Aircraft engines">aircraft engines</a> were Renault V8 units)<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> and vehicles such as the revolutionary <a href="/wiki/Renault_FT" title="Renault FT">Renault FT</a> <a href="/wiki/Tank" title="Tank">tank</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ROH_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ROH-25">[25]</a></sup> The company's military designs were so successful that Louis was awarded the <a href="/wiki/Legion_of_Honour" title="Legion of Honour">Legion of Honour</a> for his company's contributions.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> The company exported engines to American auto manufacturers for use in such automobiles as the <a href="/wiki/GJG" title="GJG">GJG</a>, which used a Renault 26&#160;hp or 40&#160;hp four-cylinder engine.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Interwar_years_.281919.E2.80.931938.29">Interwar years (1919–1938)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Interwar years (1919–1938)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg/220px-Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg" width="220" height="115" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg/330px-Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg/440px-Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="419" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Celtaquate_Berline_1935.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Renault_Celtaquatre" title="Renault Celtaquatre">Renault Celtaquatre</a>, 1935</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Louis Renault enlarged Renault's scope after 1918, producing <a href="/wiki/Agricultural_machinery" title="Agricultural machinery">agricultural</a> and industrial machinery. The war led to many new products.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup> The first Renault tractor, the Type GP was produced between 1919 and 1930. It was based on the FT tank.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup> Renault struggled to compete with the increasingly popular small, affordable "people's cars", while problems with the stock market and the workforce slowed the company's growth. Renault also had to find a way to distribute its vehicles more efficiently. In 1920, Louis signed one of its first distribution contracts with Gustave Gueudet, an entrepreneur from northern France.</p>
<p>The pre-First World War cars had a distinctive front shape caused by positioning the <a href="/wiki/Radiator_(engine_cooling)" title="Radiator (engine cooling)">radiator</a> behind the engine to give a so-called "coalscuttle" <a href="/wiki/Hood_(vehicle)" class="mw-redirect" title="Hood (vehicle)">bonnet</a>. This continued through the 1920s.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup> Only in 1930 did all models place the radiator at the front. The bonnet badge changed from circular to the familiar and continuing diamond shape in 1925.</p>
<p>Renault introduced new models at the <a href="/wiki/Paris_Motor_Show" title="Paris Motor Show">Paris Motor Show</a> that was held in September or October of the year. This led to confusion about model years. For example, a "1927" model was mostly produced in 1928.</p>
<p>Renault cars ranged from small to very large. For example, in 1928, when Renault produced 45,809 cars, its seven models started with a 6cv, a 10cv, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Monasix" title="Renault Monasix">Monasix</a>, 15cv, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Vivasix" title="Renault Vivasix">Vivasix</a>, the 18/22cv and the <a href="/wiki/Renault_40CV" title="Renault 40CV">40cv</a>. Renault offered eight body styles. The larger chassis were available to <a href="/wiki/Coachbuilder" title="Coachbuilder">coachbuilders</a>. The smaller were the most popular while the least produced was the 18/24cv. The most expensive body style in each range was the closed car. Roadsters and tourers (torpedoes) were the cheapest.</p>
<p>The London operation was important to Renault in 1928. The UK market was quite large and "colonial" modified vehicles were dispatched from there to North America. Lifted suspensions, enhanced cooling and special bodies were common on vehicles sold abroad. Exports to the US by 1928 had declined to near-zero from their high point prior to WWI. A NM 40cv Tourer had a US list price of over $4,600, about the same as a <a href="/wiki/Cadillac_V-12" title="Cadillac V-12">Cadillac V-12</a>. Closed 7-seat limousines started at $6,000 which was more expensive than a <a href="/wiki/Cadillac_V-16" title="Cadillac V-16">Cadillac V-16</a>.</p>
<p>Cars were conservatively engineered and built. The Vivasix, model PG1, was sold as the "executive sports" model beginning in 1927. Lighter weight factory steel bodies powered by a 3180 cc six-cylinder motor provided a formula that lasted until the <a href="/wiki/Second_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="Second World War">Second World War</a>.</p>
<p>The "de Grand Luxe Renaults", those with a wheelbase over 12-foot (3.7&#160;m), were produced in small numbers in two major types – six- and eight-cylinder. The 1927 six-cylinder Grand Renault models NM, PI and PZ introduced the new three spring rear suspension that considerably aided stability that was needed since some vehicles surpassed 90&#160;mph (140&#160;km/h).</p>
<p>The 8-cylinder <a href="/wiki/Renault_Reinastella" title="Renault Reinastella">Reinastella</a> was introduced in 1929 and expanded to a range culminating in the 1939 <a href="/wiki/Renault_Suprastella" title="Renault Suprastella">Suprastella</a>. Coachbuilders included Kellner, Labourdette, J. Rothschild et Fils and Renault bodies. Closed car Renault bodies were often trimmed with interior woodwork by Rothschild.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg/220px-Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg" width="220" height="292" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg/330px-Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg/440px-Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg 2x" data-file-width="753" data-file-height="1000" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Viva_Boucher.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Renault_Viva_Grand_Sport" title="Renault Viva Grand Sport">Renault Viva Grand Sport</a> and <a href="/wiki/H%C3%A9l%C3%A8ne_Boucher" title="Hélène Boucher">Hélène Boucher</a>. During the 1930s, Renault settled several speed world records with Caudron planes, thanks to its 6-cylinders engines and aerodynamic designs<sup id="cite_ref-Renault_2015_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Renault_2015-34">[34]</a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1928 Renault introduced an upgraded specification to its "Stella" line. The <a href="/wiki/Renault_Vivastella" title="Renault Vivastella">Vivastella</a>'s and Grand Renaults had upgraded interior fittings and a small star fitted above the front hood logo. This proved to be a winning differentiator and in the 1930s all cars changed to the Stella suffix from the previous two alpha character model identifiers.</p>
<p>The Grand Renaults were built using a considerable amount of aluminium. Engines, brakes, transmissions, floor and running boards and all external body panels were aluminium. Of the few that were built, many went to scrap to aid the war effort.</p>
<p>In 1931, Renault introduced diesel engines for its commercial vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-TT_26-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TT-26">[26]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault was one of the few French vehicle manufactures that pursued the production of aircraft engines after World War I. In the late 1920s it attempted to produce a high-power military engine to compete with the American <a href="/wiki/Pratt_%26_Whitney" title="Pratt &amp; Whitney">Pratt &amp; Whitney</a> units, which proved unsuccessful, although its civil engines achieved better results.<sup id="cite_ref-AERO_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AERO-35">[35]</a></sup> In the 1930s the company took over the aircraft manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Caudron" title="Caudron">Caudron</a>, focusing its production in small airplanes,<sup id="cite_ref-AERO_35-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AERO-35">[35]</a></sup> acquired a stake in <a href="/wiki/Air_France" title="Air France">Air France</a> and partnered to establish the <a href="/wiki/Airmail" title="Airmail">airmail</a> company Air-Bleu.<sup id="cite_ref-INSEE_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-INSEE-36">[36]</a></sup> Renault Caudron airplanes settled several speed world records during the 1930s. Renault continued developing tanks as part of France's rearming effort, including the <a href="/wiki/Char_D1" title="Char D1">D1</a> and the FT's replacement, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_R_35" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault R 35">R 35</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup></p>
<p>During the late 1920s and early 1930s, Renault was surpassed by <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn" title="Citroën">Citroën</a> as the largest car manufacturer in France. Citroën models at the time were more innovative and popular than Renault's.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup> However, by mid-1930s the French manufacturers were hit by the <a href="/wiki/Great_Depression" title="Great Depression">Great Depression</a>. Renault could initially offset losses through its tractor, railroad and weaponry businesses while Citroën filed for bankruptcy and was later acquired by Michelin.<sup id="cite_ref-INSEE_36-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-INSEE-36">[36]</a></sup> Renault became again the largest car manufacturer, a position it would keep until the 1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-INSEE_36-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-INSEE-36">[36]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault was finally affected by the economic crisis in 1936. The company sold Caudron and spun off its foundry and aircraft engine divisions into related but autonomous operations, keeping its core automotive business.<sup id="cite_ref-INSEE_36-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-INSEE-36">[36]</a></sup> Between 1936 and 1938, a series of labour disputes, strikes, and worker unrest spread throughout the French automobile industry.<sup id="cite_ref-Siedman1_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Siedman1-39">[39]</a></sup> The disputes were eventually quashed by Renault in a particularly intransigent way, and over 2,000 people lost their jobs.<sup id="cite_ref-Siedman1_39-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Siedman1-39">[39]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Saltmarsh2_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Saltmarsh2-40">[40]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="World_War_II_and_aftermath_.281939.E2.80.931944.29">World War II and aftermath (1939–1944)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: World War II and aftermath (1939–1944)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG/220px-Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG" width="220" height="136" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG/330px-Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG/440px-Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG 2x" data-file-width="3184" data-file-height="1964" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_4CV_BW_1.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Renault_4CV" title="Renault 4CV">Renault 4CV</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>After the <a href="/wiki/Second_Armistice_at_Compi%C3%A8gne" class="mw-redirect" title="Second Armistice at Compiègne">French capitulation in 1940</a>, Louis Renault refused to produce tanks for <a href="/wiki/Nazi_Germany" title="Nazi Germany">Nazi Germany</a>, which took control of his factories. He produced trucks instead. On 3 March 1942, the British <a href="/wiki/Royal_Air_Force" title="Royal Air Force">Royal Air Force</a> (RAF) launched 235 low-level bombers at the <a href="/wiki/%C3%8Ele_Seguin" title="Île Seguin">Billancourt</a> plant, the largest number aimed at a single target during the war.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> 460 tons of bombs were dropped on the plant and the surrounding area, causing extensive damage along with heavy civilian casualties.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup> Renault resolved to rebuild the factory as quickly as possible, but bombardments continued a year later, on 4 April, this time delivered by the Americans, and on 3 and 15 September 1943.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup></p>
<p>A few weeks after the <a href="/wiki/Liberation_of_Paris" title="Liberation of Paris">Liberation of Paris</a>, at the start of September 1944, the factory gates at Renault's Billancourt plant reopened.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup> Operations restarted slowly, in an atmosphere poisoned by plotting and political conspiracy.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup> In 1936 the Billancourt factory had been the scene of violent political and industrial unrest that had surfaced under <a href="/wiki/Leon_Blum" class="mw-redirect" title="Leon Blum">Leon Blum</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Popular_Front_(France)" title="Popular Front (France)">Popular Front</a> government. The political jostling and violence that followed liberation ostensibly reflected the rivalries between <a href="/wiki/Capitalist" class="mw-redirect" title="Capitalist">capitalist</a> collaboration and <a href="/wiki/Communist" class="mw-redirect" title="Communist">communist</a> resistance, many of the scores settled predated the invasion.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup></p>
<p>Responding to the chaotic situation at Renault, a 27 September 1944 meeting of the <a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conseil_des_ministres_(France)" class="extiw" title="fr:Conseil des ministres (France)">Council of (the provisional government's) Ministers</a> took place under <a href="/wiki/Charles_de_Gaulle" title="Charles de Gaulle">de Gaulle's</a> presidency. Postwar European politics had quickly become polarised between communists and anti-communists, and in France De Gaulle was keen to resist <a href="/wiki/French_Communist_Party" title="French Communist Party">Communist Party</a> attempts to monopolise the political dividends available to <a href="/wiki/French_resistance" class="mw-redirect" title="French resistance">resistance</a> heroes: politically Billancourt was a communist stronghold. The government decided to "requisition" the Renault factories.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup> A week later, on 4 October <a href="/wiki/Pierre_Lefaucheux" title="Pierre Lefaucheux">Pierre Lefaucheux</a>, a resistance leader with a background in engineering and top-level management, was appointed provisional administrator of the firm, assuming his responsibilities at once.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup></p>
<p>Meanwhile, the <a href="/wiki/Provisional_Government_of_the_French_Republic" title="Provisional Government of the French Republic">provisional government</a> accused Louis Renault of collaborating with the Germans. In the frenzied atmosphere of those early post-liberation days, with many wild accusations, Renault was advised by his lawyers to present himself to a judge. He appeared before Judge Marcel Martin, on 22 September 1944<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup> and was arrested on 23 September 1944, as were several other French auto-industry leaders.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup> Renault's harsh handling of the 1936–1938 strikes had left him without political allies and no one came to his aid.<sup id="cite_ref-Saltmarsh1_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Saltmarsh1-43">[43]</a></sup> He was incarcerated at <a href="/wiki/Fresnes_prison" class="mw-redirect" title="Fresnes prison">Fresnes prison</a> where he died on 24 October 1944 under unclear circumstances,<sup id="cite_ref-shame_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-shame-44">[44]</a></sup> while awaiting trial.<sup id="cite_ref-ogre_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ogre-45">[45]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup></p>
<p>On 1 January 1945, by de Gaulle's decree, the company was posthumously expropriated from Louis Renault. On 16 January 1945 it was formally nationalised as <i>Régie Nationale des Usines Renault</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1940-46_42-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1940-46-42">[42]</a></sup> Renault's were the only factories permanently expropriated by the French government.<sup id="cite_ref-Berliet_Renault_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Berliet_Renault-47">[47]</a></sup> In subsequent years, the Renault family tried to have the nationalisation rescinded by French courts and receive compensation. In 1945 and again in 1961 the Courts responded that they had no authority to review the government's actions.<sup id="cite_ref-Saltmarsh1_43-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Saltmarsh1-43">[43]</a></sup></p>

</div>

</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG/220px-Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG/330px-Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG/440px-Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2272" data-file-height="1704" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_R8_Gordini_Lahti.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
1964 <a href="/wiki/Renault_R8_Gordini" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault R8 Gordini">Renault R8 Gordini</a> was the first sportive compact car for a public consumption price.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Postwar_resurgence_.281945.E2.80.931971.29">Postwar resurgence (1945–1971)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Postwar resurgence (1945–1971)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Under the leadership of <a href="/wiki/Pierre_Lefaucheux" title="Pierre Lefaucheux">Pierre Lefaucheux</a>, Renault experienced both a commercial resurgence and <a href="/wiki/Labor_unrest" title="Labor unrest">labor unrest</a>, that was ultimately to continue into the 1980s.</p>
<p>In secrecy during the war, Louis Renault had developed the <a href="/wiki/Rear_engine" class="mw-redirect" title="Rear engine">rear engine</a> <a href="/wiki/Renault_4CV" title="Renault 4CV">4CV</a><sup id="cite_ref-Autoworld197404_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Autoworld197404-49">[49]</a></sup> which was subsequently launched under Lefacheux in 1946. Renault debuted its flagship model, the largely conventional 2-litre 4-cylinder <a href="/wiki/Renault_Fr%C3%A9gate" title="Renault Frégate">Renault Frégate</a> (1951–1960), shortly thereafter. The 4CV proved a capable rival for cars such as the <a href="/wiki/Morris_Minor" title="Morris Minor">Morris Minor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Beetle" title="Volkswagen Beetle">Volkswagen Beetle</a>; its sales of more than half a million ensured its production until 1961.</p>
<p>After the success of the 4CV, Lefacheux continued to defy the postwar French <a href="/wiki/Paul-Marie_Pons" title="Paul-Marie Pons">Ministry of Industrial Production</a>, which had wanted to convert Renault solely to truck manufacture,<sup id="cite_ref-50jahre_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50jahre-50">[50]</a></sup> by directing the development of its successor. He oversaw the prototyping of the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Dauphine" title="Renault Dauphine">Dauphine</a> (until <a href="/wiki/Pierre_Lefaucheux#Death" title="Pierre Lefaucheux">his death</a>), enlisting the help of artist <a href="/wiki/Paule_Marrot" title="Paule Marrot">Paule Marrot</a> in <a href="/wiki/Renault_Dauphine#Paule_Marrot" title="Renault Dauphine">pioneering the company's textile and color division</a>.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Renault_Dauphine" title="Renault Dauphine">Dauphine</a> sold well as the company expanded production and sales further abroad, including Africa and North America.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup> The Dauphine sold well initially in the US, although it subsequently became outdated against increased competition, including from the country's nascent domestic compacts such as the <a href="/wiki/Chevrolet_Corvair" title="Chevrolet Corvair">Chevrolet Corvair</a>. Renault also sold the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Caravelle" title="Renault Caravelle">Renault Caravelle</a> roadster, which was called the Floride outside North America.</p>
<p>During the 1950s, Renault absorbed small French heavy vehicles' manufacturers (<a href="/wiki/Somua" title="Somua">Somua</a> and <a href="/wiki/Latil" title="Latil">Latil</a>) and in 1955 merged them with its own truck and bus division to form the <a href="/wiki/Saviem" title="Saviem">Société Anonyme de Véhicules Industriels et d'Equipements Mécaniques</a> (Saviem).<sup id="cite_ref-CBTT_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CBTT-52">[52]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault then launched two successful cars – the <a href="/wiki/Renault_4" title="Renault 4">Renault 4</a> (1961–1992), a practical competitor for the likes of the <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn_2CV" title="Citroën 2CV">Citroën 2CV</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Renault_8" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 8">Renault 8</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup> The larger rear-engined Renault 10 followed the success of the R8, and was the last rear-engined Renault. The company achieved success with the more modern and more upmarket <a href="/wiki/Renault_16" title="Renault 16">Renault 16</a>, a pioneering <a href="/wiki/Hatchback" title="Hatchback">hatchback</a> launched in 1966, followed by the smaller <a href="/wiki/Renault_6" title="Renault 6">Renault 6</a>.</p>
<p>On 16 January 1970 the manufacturer celebrated the 25th anniversary of its 1945 rebirth as the nationalised <i>Régie Nationale des Usines Renault</i>. The 1960s had been a decade of aggressive growth: a few months earlier, in October 1969, the manufacturer had launched the <a href="/wiki/Renault_12" title="Renault 12">Renault 12</a>, combining the engineering philosophy of its hatch-backs with the more conservative "three-box" design. The four-door <a href="/wiki/Renault_12" title="Renault 12">Renault 12</a> model fit between the <a href="/wiki/Renault_6" title="Renault 6">Renault 6</a> and <a href="/wiki/Renault_16" title="Renault 16">Renault 16</a>. The model was a success. 1970 was also the first year during which Renault produced more than a million cars in a single year, building 1,055,803.<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1970_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1970-53">[53]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Modern_era_.281972.E2.80.931980.29">Modern era (1972–1980)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Modern era (1972–1980)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_5_Maxiturbo_Jarama_2006e.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Renault_5_Maxiturbo_Jarama_2006e.jpg/220px-Renault_5_Maxiturbo_Jarama_2006e.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Renault_5_Maxiturbo_Jarama_2006e.jpg/330px-Renault_5_Maxiturbo_Jarama_2006e.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Renault_5_Maxiturbo_Jarama_2006e.jpg/440px-Renault_5_Maxiturbo_Jarama_2006e.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2046" data-file-height="1364" /></a>

Renault 5 Turbo</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_R17.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Renault_R17.jpg/220px-Renault_R17.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Renault_R17.jpg/330px-Renault_R17.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Renault_R17.jpg/440px-Renault_R17.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a>

1974 <a href="/wiki/Renault_17" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 17">Renault 17</a> coupe</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:RENAULT_FUEGO_(5201417780).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/RENAULT_FUEGO_%285201417780%29.jpg/220px-RENAULT_FUEGO_%285201417780%29.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/RENAULT_FUEGO_%285201417780%29.jpg/330px-RENAULT_FUEGO_%285201417780%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/RENAULT_FUEGO_%285201417780%29.jpg/440px-RENAULT_FUEGO_%285201417780%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="683" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:RENAULT_FUEGO_(5201417780).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/Renault_Fuego" title="Renault Fuego">Renault Fuego</a> won 8 consecutive championships in the <a href="/wiki/TC_2000_Championship" title="TC 2000 Championship">TC 2000</a> touring car racing series between 1986 and 1993</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The company's compact and economical <a href="/wiki/Renault_5" title="Renault 5">Renault 5</a> model, launched in January 1972,<sup id="cite_ref-Automobilia1972_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Automobilia1972-54">[54]</a></sup> was another success, anticipating the <a href="/wiki/1973_energy_crisis" class="mw-redirect" title="1973 energy crisis">1973 energy crisis</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup> Throughout the 1970s the R4, R5, R6, R12, R15, R16 and R17 maintained Renault's production with new models including the <a href="/wiki/Renault_18" title="Renault 18">Renault 18</a> and <a href="/wiki/Renault_20" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 20">Renault 20</a>.</p>
<p>During the mid seventies the already broad-based company diversified into more industries and continued to expand globally, including <a href="/wiki/South_East_Asia" class="mw-redirect" title="South East Asia">South East Asia</a>. The energy crisis led Renault to again attempt to attack the North American market. Despite the Dauphine's success in the United States in the late 1950s and an unsuccessful assembly project in <a href="/wiki/Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville,_Quebec" class="mw-redirect" title="Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville, Quebec">Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville, Quebec</a>, (1964–72), Renault began to disappear from North America at the end of the decade.</p>
<p>Over the decades Renault had developed a collaborative partnership with <a href="/wiki/Nash_Motors" title="Nash Motors">Nash Motors</a> <a href="/wiki/Nash_Rambler" title="Nash Rambler">Rambler</a> and its successor <a href="/wiki/American_Motors_Corporation" class="mw-redirect" title="American Motors Corporation">American Motors Corporation</a> (AMC). From 1962 to 1967, Renault assembled <a href="/wiki/Complete_knock_down" class="mw-redirect" title="Complete knock down">complete knock down</a> (CKD) kits of the <a href="/wiki/Rambler_Classic" title="Rambler Classic">Rambler Classic</a> sedans in its factory in Belgium.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup> Renault did not have large or luxury cars in its product line and the "Rambler Renault" was positioned as an alternative to the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_Heckflosse" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz Heckflosse">Mercedes-Benz "Fintail"</a> cars. Later, Renault continued to make and sell a hybrid of AMC's <a href="/wiki/Rambler_American" title="Rambler American">Rambler American</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rambler_Classic" title="Rambler Classic">Rambler Classic</a> called the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Torino" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault Torino">Renault Torino</a> in Argentina (sold through IKA-Renault). Renault partnered with AMC on other projects, such as a rotary concept engine in the late 1960s.</p>
<p>In the late 1960s and 1970s the company established subsidiaries in <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Europe" title="Eastern Europe">Eastern Europe</a>, most notably <a href="/wiki/Dacia_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Dacia (car)">Dacia</a> in Romania, and <a href="/wiki/Industrias_Kaiser_Argentina" title="Industrias Kaiser Argentina">South America</a> (many of which remain active) and forged technological cooperation agreements with <a href="/wiki/Volvo" title="Volvo">Volvo</a> and <a href="/wiki/Peugeot" title="Peugeot">Peugeot</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-DTI_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DTI-56">[56]</a></sup> (for instance, for the development of the <a href="/wiki/PRV_engine" class="mw-redirect" title="PRV engine">PRV</a> <a href="/wiki/V6" class="mw-redirect" title="V6">V6</a> engine, which was used in <a href="/wiki/Renault_30" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 30">Renault 30</a>, <a href="/wiki/Peugeot_604" title="Peugeot 604">Peugeot 604</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Volvo_200_series" class="mw-redirect" title="Volvo 200 series">Volvo 260</a> in the late 1970s).</p>
<p>In the mid-1960s Renault Australia was set up in Melbourne. The company produced and assembled models including the R8, R10, R12, R16, sporty R15, R17 coupe's, R18 and R20. The unit closed in 1981. Renault Australia also built and marketed Peugeots. From 1977, they assembled <a href="/wiki/Ford_Cortina" title="Ford Cortina">Ford Cortina</a> station wagons under contract- the loss of this contract ended the factory.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2011)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>When Peugeot acquired Citroën and formed PSA, the group's collaboration with Renault was reduced, although established joint production projects were maintained. Prior its merging with Peugeot, Citroën sold to Renault the truck and bus manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Berliet" title="Berliet">Berliet</a> in 1975,<sup id="cite_ref-DTI_56-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DTI-56">[56]</a></sup> merging it with its subsidiary Saviem in 1978 to create <a href="/wiki/Renault_Trucks" title="Renault Trucks">Renault Véhicules Industriels</a>, which became the only French manufacturer of heavy commercial vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-TT_26-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TT-26">[26]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-CBTT_52-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CBTT-52">[52]</a></sup> In 1976, Renault reorganised the company into four business areas: automobiles (for car and <a href="/wiki/Light_commercial_vehicles" class="mw-redirect" title="Light commercial vehicles">light commercial vehicles</a> or LCVs), finance and services, commercial vehicles (coaches and trucks over 2.5 <a href="/wiki/Metric_ton" class="mw-redirect" title="Metric ton">tons</a> <a href="/wiki/Gross_vehicle_weight_rating" title="Gross vehicle weight rating">GVW</a>), and minor operations under an industrial enterprises division (farm machinery, plastics, foundry, etc.). In 1980, Renault produced 2,053,677 cars and LCVs. The cars at the time were the Renault 4, 5, 6, 7, 12, 14, 16, 18, 20 and 30; the LCVs were the 4, 5 and 12 Société and the Estafette. The company added 54,086 buses/coaches and trucks.<sup id="cite_ref-DTI_56-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DTI-56">[56]</a></sup></p>
<p>In North America, Renault partnered with American Motors, lending AMC operating capital and buying a minority 22.5% stake in the company in late 1979. The first Renault model sold through AMC's dealerships was the R5, renamed Renault Le Car. Jeep was keeping AMC afloat until new products, particularly the XJ Cherokee, could be launched. When the bottom fell out of the 4×4 truck market in early 1980 AMC was in danger of bankruptcy. To protect its investment, Renault bailed AMC out with cash – at the price of a controlling 47.5% interest.<sup id="cite_ref-TCAMAIH_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TCAMAIH-57">[57]</a></sup> Renault replaced some AMC executives, and Jose J. Dedeurwaerder of Renault became President of AMC.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup></p>
<p>The partnership resulted in the marketing of <a href="/wiki/Jeep" title="Jeep">Jeep</a> vehicles in Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Jeep_Cherokee_(XJ)" title="Jeep Cherokee (XJ)">Jeep XJ Cherokee</a> may have been a joint AMC/Renault project, since some early sketches of the XJ series were made in collaboration by Renault and AMC engineers (AMC insisted that the XJ Cherokee was designed by AMC personnel; even though a former Renault engineer designed the Quadra-Link front suspension for the XJ series).<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup> The Jeep also used wheels and seats from Renault. Part of AMC's overall strategy was to save manufacturing cost by using Renault parts and engineering expertise when practical. This led to the improvement of the venerable <a href="/wiki/AMC_Straight-6_engine" class="mw-redirect" title="AMC Straight-6 engine">AMC in-line six</a> – a Renault/Bendix-based port electronic fuel injection system (usually called <a href="/wiki/Renix" title="Renix">Renix</a>) transformed it into a modern, competitive powerplant with a jump from 110 to 177&#160;hp (82 to 132&#160;kW) with less displacement (from 4.2L to 4.0L). The XJC Cherokee concept which was conceived in 1983 as a successor to the XJ series was also a joint collaboration with AMC and Renault engineers until the design was inherited by the Chrysler Corporation in late 1987 after Renault divested AMC - which debuted in 1989 as the Jeep Concept 1 (evolving into the <a href="/wiki/Jeep_Grand_Cherokee" title="Jeep Grand Cherokee">Jeep Grand Cherokee</a> in April 1992).</p>
<p>The Renault-AMC marketing effort in passenger cars was not successful compared to the popularity for Jeep vehicles. This was because by the time the Renault range was ready, the <a href="/wiki/1979_energy_crisis" title="1979 energy crisis">second energy crisis</a> was over, taking with it much of the desire for economical, compact cars. One exception was the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Alliance" title="Renault Alliance">Renault Alliance</a> (an Americanised version of the <a href="/wiki/Renault_9" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 9">Renault 9</a>), which debuted for the 1983 model year. Assembled at AMC's <a href="/wiki/Kenosha,_Wisconsin" title="Kenosha, Wisconsin">Kenosha, Wisconsin</a> plant,<sup id="cite_ref-TCAMAIH_57-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TCAMAIH-57">[57]</a></sup> the Alliance received <a href="/wiki/Motor_Trend" title="Motor Trend">Motor Trend</a>'s domestic <a href="/wiki/Motor_Trend_Car_of_the_Year" title="Motor Trend Car of the Year">Car of The Year</a> award in 1983.<sup id="cite_ref-Renault_car_of_the_year_USA_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Renault_car_of_the_year_USA-59">[59]</a></sup> The Alliance's 72% U.S. content allowed it to qualify as a domestic vehicle, making it the first car with a foreign nameplate to win the award. (In 2000, <i>Motor Trend</i> did away with separate awards for domestic and imported vehicles.)</p>
<p>US releases in the 1980s included the Renault Alliance GTA and GTA convertible – an automatic-top convertible with a 2.0&#160;L engine – big for a car of its class and the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Fuego" title="Renault Fuego">Renault Fuego</a> coupe. The Alliance was followed by the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Encore" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault Encore">Encore</a> (U.S. version of the <a href="/wiki/Renault_11" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 11">Renault 11</a>), an Alliance-based hatchback.<sup id="cite_ref-TCAMAIH_57-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TCAMAIH-57">[57]</a></sup> In 1982 Renault become the second European automaker to build cars in the United States, after <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen" title="Volkswagen">Volkswagen</a>. However, Renaults quickly became the target of customer complaints for poor quality and sales plummeted.</p>
<p>Eventually, Renault sold AMC to <a href="/wiki/Chrysler_Corporation" class="mw-redirect" title="Chrysler Corporation">Chrysler</a> in 1987 after the assassination of Renault's chairman, <a href="/wiki/Georges_Besse" title="Georges Besse">Georges Besse</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Renault_Medallion" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault Medallion">Renault Medallion</a> (Renault 21 in Europe) sedan and wagon was sold from 1987 to 1989 through <a href="/wiki/Jeep-Eagle" title="Jeep-Eagle">Jeep-Eagle</a> dealerships. Jeep-Eagle was the division Chrysler created out of the former American Motors. Renault imports ended after 1989. A completely new <a href="/wiki/Full-size_car" title="Full-size car">full-sized</a> 4-door sedan, the <a href="/wiki/Eagle_Premier" title="Eagle Premier">Eagle Premier</a>, was developed during the partnership between AMC and Renault. The Premier design, as well as its state-of-the-art manufacturing facility in <a href="/wiki/Bramalea,_Ontario" title="Bramalea, Ontario">Bramalea</a>, Ontario, Canada, were the starting point for the sleek <a href="/wiki/Chrysler_LH_platform" title="Chrysler LH platform">LH sedans</a> such as the <a href="/wiki/Eagle_Vision" title="Eagle Vision">Eagle Vision</a> and <a href="/wiki/Chrysler_300M" title="Chrysler 300M">Chrysler 300M</a>.</p>
<p>In early 1979, as part of its attempts to expand into the American market, Renault bought a 20% minority stake in the truck manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Mack_Trucks" title="Mack Trucks">Mack Trucks</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-RCICIUSJWE_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RCICIUSJWE-60">[60]</a></sup> The aim of this operation was to make use of the company's extensive delearship network to distribute light trucks.<sup id="cite_ref-TMC_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TMC-61">[61]</a></sup> In 1983, Renault increased its stake in Mack Trucks to 44.6%.<sup id="cite_ref-RCICIUSJWE_60-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RCICIUSJWE-60">[60]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-TMC_61-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TMC-61">[61]</a></sup> In 1987, it transferred the ownership of a 42% stake to Renault Véhicules Industriels.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the late seventies and early eighties Renault increased its involvement in motorsport, with novel inventions such as <a href="/wiki/Turbochargers" class="mw-redirect" title="Turbochargers">turbochargers</a> in their <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> cars. Renault's head of engines, Georges Douin, orchestrated the installation of turbocharged engines across much of the Renault range beginning in 1980. 10% of all turbocharged European cars in 1984 were Renaults.<sup id="cite_ref-Car9.84_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Car9.84-63">[63]</a></sup> The company's road car designs were revolutionary in other ways also – the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Espace" title="Renault Espace">Renault Espace</a> was one of the first <a href="/wiki/Minivan" title="Minivan">minivans</a> and was to remain the most well-known minivan in Europe for the next two decades. The second-generation Renault 5, the European Car of the Year-winning <a href="/wiki/Renault_9" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 9">Renault 9</a>, and the most luxurious Renault yet, the aerodynamic <a href="/wiki/Renault_25" title="Renault 25">25</a> were all released in the early 1980s. At the same time poor product quality damaged the brand. The ill-fated <a href="/wiki/Renault_14" title="Renault 14">Renault 14</a> may have been the culmination of these problems in the early 1980s.</p>

</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Restructuring_.281981.E2.80.931995.29">Restructuring (1981–1995)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Restructuring (1981–1995)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renaults were somewhat successful on both road and track, including the 1984 <a href="/wiki/Renault_Espace" title="Renault Espace">Espace</a> launch, which was Europe's first multi-purpose vehicle, a dozen years before any competitor. However, Renault was losing a billion francs a month totaling 12.5&#160;billion in 1984. The government intervened and <a href="/wiki/Georges_Besse" title="Georges Besse">Georges Besse</a> was installed as chairman; he set about cutting costs dramatically, selling many of Renault's non-core assets (Volvo stake, <a href="/wiki/Gitane" title="Gitane">Gitane</a>, Eurocar and Renix), withdrawing almost entirely from <a href="/wiki/Motorsports" class="mw-redirect" title="Motorsports">motorsports</a> and laying off many employees.<sup id="cite_ref-R1985_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-R1985-64">[64]</a></sup> This halved the deficit by 1986, but Besse was murdered by the communist <a href="/wiki/Terrorist" class="mw-redirect" title="Terrorist">terrorist</a> group <i><a href="/wiki/Action_Directe_(terrorist_group)" class="mw-redirect" title="Action Directe (terrorist group)">Action Directe</a></i> in November 1986. He was replaced by Raymond Lévy, who continued Besse's initiatives, slimming the company enough that by the end of 1987, Renault was more or less financially stable. However, while Besse was convinced that Renault needed a presence in the North American market and wanted to push forward with restructuring <a href="/wiki/American_Motors" title="American Motors">American Motors</a>, Lévy, facing domestic losses from Renault at home, and losses from American Motors in the United States, along with the political climate that led to Besse's assassination, decided to sell American Motors to <a href="/wiki/Chrysler" title="Chrysler">Chrysler</a> that same year.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Renault_9" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 9">Renault 9</a>, a small four-door family saloon, was voted <a href="/wiki/European_Car_of_the_Year" title="European Car of the Year">European Car of the Year</a> on its 1981 launch. It sold well in <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a>, but was eventually eclipsed by the <a href="/wiki/Renault_11" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 11">Renault 11</a> hatchback, as the hatchback bodystyle became more popular on this size of car. The <a href="/wiki/Renault_5" title="Renault 5">Renault 5</a> entered its second generation in 1984 and continued to sell well. The long-running <a href="/wiki/Renault_18" title="Renault 18">Renault 18</a> was replaced by the <a href="/wiki/Renault_21" title="Renault 21">Renault 21</a> early in 1986, adding a seven-seater estate badged as the Nevada or Savanna depending on where it was sold. Renault's top of the range model in the 1980s was the <a href="/wiki/Renault_25" title="Renault 25">Renault 25</a>, launched at the end of 1983.</p>
<p>In 1990, Renault strengthened its collaboration with Volvo by signing an agreement that allowed both companies to reduce vehicle conception costs and purchasing expenses. Renault had access to Volvo expertise in upper market segments and in return Volvo exploited Renault designs for low and medium segments. In 1993 the two companies announced their intention to merge operations by 1 January 1994 and increased their cross-shareholding. The French accepted the merger, while Volvo shareholders rejected it.<sup id="cite_ref-R1985_64-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-R1985-64">[64]</a></sup></p>
<p>A revitalised Renault launched successful new cars in the early 1990s, accompanied by an improved marketing effort on European markets,<sup id="cite_ref-R1985_64-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-R1985-64">[64]</a></sup> including the 5 replacement, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Clio" title="Renault Clio">Clio</a> in May 1990.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup> The Clio was the first new model of a generation that replaced numeric identifiers with traditional nameplates. The Clio was voted <a href="/wiki/European_Car_of_the_Year" title="European Car of the Year">European Car of the Year</a> soon after its launch, and was one of Europe's best selling cars in the 1990s, proving even more popular than its predecessor. Other important launches included the third-generation <a href="/wiki/Renault_Espace" title="Renault Espace">Espace</a> in 1996 and the innovative <a href="/wiki/Renault_Twingo" title="Renault Twingo">Twingo</a> in 1992, the first car to be marketed as a city car MPV. The Twingo was roomier than any prior cars of its size range. Twingo sales reached 2.4 million in Europe, even though the original was only built for (Continental) left-hand drive markets.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup></p>
