<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Privatisation_and_the_alliance_era_.281996.E2.80.93present.29">Privatisation and the alliance era (1996–present)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Privatisation and the alliance era (1996–present)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>It was eventually decided that the company's state-owned status was a detriment. By 1994 plans to sell shares to public investors were officially announced.<sup id="cite_ref-R1985_64-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-R1985-64">[64]</a></sup> The company was <a href="/wiki/Privatization" title="Privatization">privatised</a> in 1996.<sup id="cite_ref-IDCH_31-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IDCH-31">[31]</a></sup> This new freedom allowed the company to venture once again into markets in Eastern Europe and South America, including a new factory in Brazil and upgrades for its infrastructure in Argentina and Turkey. In December 1996 <a href="/wiki/General_Motors_Europe" title="General Motors Europe">General Motors Europe</a> and Renault begun to collaborate in the development of LCVs, starting with the second generation <a href="/wiki/Renault_Trafic" title="Renault Trafic">Trafic</a> (codenamed X83).<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault's financial problems were not all fixed by the privatisation, and Renault's President, <a href="/wiki/Louis_Schweitzer_(businessman)" title="Louis Schweitzer (businessman)">Louis Schweitzer</a> gave to his then deputy, <a href="/wiki/Carlos_Ghosn" title="Carlos Ghosn">Carlos Ghosn</a>, the task of confronting them. Ghosn elaborated a plan to cut costs for the period 1998–2000, reducing the workforce, revising production processes, standardising vehicle parts and pushing the launch of new models. The company also undertook organisational changes, introducing a <a href="/wiki/Lean_manufacturing" title="Lean manufacturing">lean production system</a> with delegate responsibilities inspired by Japanese systems (the "Renault Production Way"), reforming work methods and centralising <a href="/wiki/Research_and_development" title="Research and development">research and development</a> at its Technocentre to reduce vehicle conception costs while accelerating such conception.<sup id="cite_ref-R1985_64-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-R1985-64">[64]</a></sup></p>
<p>After Volvo's exit, Renault searched for a new partner to cope with an industry that was consolidating. Talks with BMW, Mitsubishi, Nissan, PSA and others were held yielded a relationship with Nissan, whose negotiations with <a href="/wiki/Daimler_AG" title="Daimler AG">Daimler</a> had stalled.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup> Signed on 27 March 1999, the <a href="/wiki/Renault%E2%80%93Nissan_Alliance" title="Renault–Nissan Alliance">Renault–Nissan Alliance</a> is the first of its kind involving a Japanese and a French company, including cross-ownership. Renault initially acquired a 36.8% stake at a cost of US$3.5&#160;billion in Nissan, while Nissan in turn took a 15% non-voting stake in Renault. Renault continued to operate as a stand-alone company, but with the intent to collaborate with its alliance partner to reduce costs. The same year Renault bought a 51% majority stake of the Romanian company <a href="/wiki/Automobile_Dacia" title="Automobile Dacia">Dacia</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-DEVELOPING_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DEVELOPING-71">[71]</a></sup> thus returning after 30 years, in which time the Romanians had built over 2 million cars that primarily consisted of local version of Renaults 8, 12 and 20. In 2000, Renault acquired a controlling stake of the South Korean <a href="/wiki/Samsung_Group" class="mw-redirect" title="Samsung Group">Samsung Group</a>'s automotive division.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the late 1990s and early 2000s, Renault sold various assets to finance its inversions and acquisitions,<sup id="cite_ref-SELLOFF_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SELLOFF-73">[73]</a></sup> refocusing itself as a car and van manufacturer. In 1999, the company sold its <a href="/wiki/Industrial_automation" class="mw-redirect" title="Industrial automation">industrial automation</a> subsidiary, Renault Automation, to <a href="/wiki/Comau" title="Comau">Comau</a> and its engine parts division to TWR Engine Components.<sup id="cite_ref-SELLOFF_73-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SELLOFF-73">[73]</a></sup> In 2001, Renault sold its 50% stake in bus/coach manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Iveco_Bus" title="Iveco Bus">Irisbus</a> to co-owner <a href="/wiki/Iveco" title="Iveco">Iveco</a> and its <a href="/wiki/Logistics" title="Logistics">logistics</a> subsidiary CAT France to Global Automotive Logistics.<sup id="cite_ref-SELLOFF_73-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SELLOFF-73">[73]</a></sup> Following the sale of Renault Véhicules Industriels to Volvo in 2001, the company retained a minority (but controlling) stake (20%) in the Volvo Group. In 2010 Renault reduced its participation to 6.5% and in December 2012 sold its remaining shares.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup> In 2004, Renault sold a 51% majority stake in its agricultural machinery division, Renault Agriculture, to CLAAS. In 2006, CLAAS increased its ownership to 80% and in 2008 took full control.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the twenty-first century, Renault developed a reputation for distinctive, outlandish design. The second generation of the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Laguna" title="Renault Laguna">Laguna</a> and Mégane featured ambitious, angular designs that turned out to be successful, The 2000 Laguna was the second European car to feature "keyless" entry and ignition.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup> Less successful were the company's more upmarket models. The <a href="/wiki/Renault_Avantime" title="Renault Avantime">Avantime</a>, a unique <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coupé">coupé</a> / <a href="/wiki/Multi-purpose_vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Multi-purpose vehicle">multi-purpose vehicle</a>, sold poorly and was quickly discontinued while the luxury <a href="/wiki/Renault_Vel_Satis" title="Renault Vel Satis">Vel Satis</a> model also disappointed. However, the design inspired the lines of the second-generation Mégane, the maker's most successful car. As well as its distinctive styling, Renault was to become known for its car safety by the independent company EuroNCAP<sup id="cite_ref-Renault-safety-leader-NCAP_77-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Renault-safety-leader-NCAP-77">[77]</a></sup> Thus, in 2001, the Laguna achieved a 5-star rating,<sup id="cite_ref-Renault-safety-leader-NCAP_77-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Renault-safety-leader-NCAP-77">[77]</a></sup> followed in 2004 by the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Modus" title="Renault Modus">Modus</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup></p>
<p>In April 2010, Renault-Nissan announced an alliance with <a href="/wiki/Daimler_AG" title="Daimler AG">Daimler</a>. Renault supplied Mercedes-Benz with its brand new 1.6 L turbodiesel engine and Mercedes-Benz provided a 2.0 L four-cylinder petrol engine to Renault-Nissan.<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup> The resulting new alliance was to develop a replacement for the <a href="/wiki/Smart_(automobile)" class="mw-redirect" title="Smart (automobile)">Smart</a> based on the Twingo.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup></p>
<p>In February 2010, Renault opened a new production factory near <a href="/wiki/Tangier" title="Tangier">Tangier</a>, <a href="/wiki/Morocco" title="Morocco">Morocco</a>, with an annual output capacity of 170,000 vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup> Initially, it manufactured the <a href="/wiki/Dacia_Lodgy" title="Dacia Lodgy">Dacia Lodgy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dacia_Dokker" title="Dacia Dokker">Dacia Dokker</a> models followed in October 2013<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup> by the second generation <a href="/wiki/Dacia_Sandero" title="Dacia Sandero">Dacia Sandero</a>. The output capacity increased to 340,000 vehicles per year with the inauguration of a second production line.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup> The site is located in a dedicated <a href="/wiki/Free_trade_area" class="mw-redirect" title="Free trade area">free trade area</a>, neighboring Tanger Automotive City.<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">[84]</a></sup> According to Renault, the new factory emits zero carbon and industrial liquid discharges.<sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup> Over 100,000 vehicles were produced there in 2013. Renault expects to eventually increase production at the Tangier plant to 400,000 vehicles per year.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">[86]</a></sup></p>
<p>In December 2012 the Algeria's National Investment Fund (FNI), the <a href="/wiki/SNVI" title="SNVI">Société Nationale de Véhicules Industriels</a> (SNVI), and Renault signed an agreement to establish a factory near the city of <a href="/wiki/Oran" title="Oran">Oran</a>, Algeria, with the aim of manufacturing Symbol units from 2014 onwards. The production output was estimated at 25,000 vehicles. The Algerian State has a 51% stake in the facility.<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">[88]</a></sup></p>
<p>In September 2013, Renault launched its brand in <a href="/wiki/Indonesia" title="Indonesia">Indonesia</a>, the world's fourth most populous country, with the aim of becoming one of the top European brands there until 2016. The model range at the time of the launch consisted of the <a href="/wiki/Dacia_Duster" title="Dacia Duster">Duster</a> (locally assembled), the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Koleos" title="Renault Koleos">Koleos</a> and the <a href="/wiki/M%C3%A9gane_Renault_Sport" title="Mégane Renault Sport">Mégane RS</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup> Later, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Clio" title="Renault Clio">Clio</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Captur" title="Renault Captur">Captur</a> were also added.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">[90]</a></sup></p>
<p>In April 2015, the <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">French</a> government upped their stake in Renault to 19.73 percent with the aim of blocking a resolution at the next annual general meeting that could reduce its control over the company.<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup></p>
<p>During 2016, Renault changed position on the viability of <a href="/wiki/B-segment" title="B-segment">small</a> diesel cars in Europe, as they become significantly more expensive when re-engineered to comply with <a href="/wiki/Euro6" class="mw-redirect" title="Euro6">new emissions regulations</a> as a result of the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_emissions_scandal" title="Volkswagen emissions scandal">Volkswagen emissions scandal</a>. Renault believes that all small and some <a href="/wiki/C-segment" title="C-segment">mid-size</a> will no longer be diesels by 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">[92]</a></sup> However, on Friday, 13 January 2017, Renault shares fell as the <a href="/wiki/Judiciary_of_France" title="Judiciary of France">Paris prosecutor</a> started an investigation into possible exhaust emissions cheating.<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">[93]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94">[94]</a></sup> Renault denied any foul play, stating compliance with French and European standards.<sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95">[95]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Innovations">Innovations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Innovations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<ul>
<li>1899&#160;: Louis Renault "Driving, speed-changing mechanism and reversing gear"<sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96">[96]</a></sup> Louis Renault invented a revolutionary <i>direct drive</i> gear<sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">[97]</a></sup> with no drive belt, with much better uphill performances.</li>
<li>1963: <a href="/wiki/Renault_8" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 8">Renault 8</a> was the first serial car with four-wheel disc brake system</li>
<li>1980&#160;: First patents for "Braking distribution device for total adherence"<sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">[98]</a></sup>&#160;<b>·</b> <sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">[99]</a></sup></li>
<li>1988&#160;: CARMINAT, a real-time system for location and weather information. This program received European support from 1988, under the code Eureka EU-55 CARMINAT.<sup id="cite_ref-Carminat_Renault_system_100-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Carminat_Renault_system-100">[100]</a></sup> These innovations for the real-time location and human-machine interfaces are included in the Renault R-link system and Carminat Tom-Tom devices.</li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsport">Motorsport</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Motorsport">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault8.12.09.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/83/Renault8.12.09.jpg/220px-Renault8.12.09.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/83/Renault8.12.09.jpg/330px-Renault8.12.09.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/83/Renault8.12.09.jpg/440px-Renault8.12.09.jpg 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="400" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault8.12.09.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
1907 Renault-built Replica of their <a href="/wiki/French_Grand_Prix" title="French Grand Prix">French Grand Prix</a> winner, one of 4 known to exist</div>
</div>
</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Renault_Sport" title="Renault Sport">Renault Sport</a> and <a href="/wiki/Formula_Renault" title="Formula Renault">Formula Renault</a></div>
<p>Renault took part in motorsport at the beginning of the 20th century, promoted by <a href="/wiki/Marcel_Renault" title="Marcel Renault">Marcel Renault</a>'s racing interests and over the years acquired companies with a sporting connection such as <a href="/wiki/Gordini" title="Gordini">Gordini</a> and <a href="/wiki/Alpine_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Alpine (car)">Alpine</a>.</p>
<p>In the seventies, Renault set up a dedicated motorsport division called <a href="/wiki/Renault_Sport" title="Renault Sport">Renault Sport</a>, and won the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Le_Mans" title="24 Hours of Le Mans">Le Mans 24 Hours</a> with the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Alpine_A442" title="Renault Alpine A442">Renault Alpine A442</a> in 1978. Renault achieved success in both <a href="/wiki/Rallying" title="Rallying">rallying</a> and in <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> over decades.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:257px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg/255px-Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg" width="255" height="191" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg/383px-Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg/510px-Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2560" data-file-height="1913" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_RS7_rear_Donington_Grand_Prix_Collection.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Renault has twelve F1 Championships wins as engine manufacturer in Formula One.<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101">[101]</a></sup> Nigel Mansell, Damon Hill, Michael Schumacher, Alain Prost, Fernando Alonso, Sebastian Vettel and Jacques Villeneuve won eleven F1 driver's titles with cars powered by Renault engines.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg/220px-Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg" width="220" height="137" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg/330px-Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg/440px-Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3874" data-file-height="2405" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Alpine_A442B_at_Goodwood_2014_004.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/Renault_Alpine_A442" title="Renault Alpine A442">Renault Alpine A442</a>, 1978 <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Le_Mans" title="24 Hours of Le Mans">Le Mans 24 Hours</a> winner, at the 2014 <a href="/wiki/Goodwood_festival_of_speed" class="mw-redirect" title="Goodwood festival of speed">Goodwood festival of speed</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The company has also backed various one-make single-seater series such as <a href="/wiki/Formula_Renault" title="Formula Renault">Formula Renault</a> and the <a href="/wiki/World_Series_by_Renault" class="mw-redirect" title="World Series by Renault">Formula Renault 3.5</a>. These two racing series were a step in the career of thousands of drivers, including Formula One champions <a href="/wiki/Fernando_Alonso" title="Fernando Alonso">Fernando Alonso</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sebastian_Vettel" title="Sebastian Vettel">Sebastian Vettel</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kimi_R%C3%A4ikk%C3%B6nen" title="Kimi Räikkönen">Kimi Räikkönen</a><sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">[102]</a></sup> or <a href="/wiki/Lewis_Hamilton" title="Lewis Hamilton">Lewis Hamilton</a><sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">[103]</a></sup> or <a href="/wiki/IndyCar" class="mw-redirect" title="IndyCar">IndyCar</a> champion <a href="/wiki/Will_Power" title="Will Power">Will Power</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-104" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-104">[104]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault Sport develops and manufactures the Renault Sport-badged cars,<sup id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105">[105]</a></sup> as the Renault Clio RS (for Renault Sport) and the <a href="/wiki/M%C3%A9gane_Renault_Sport" title="Mégane Renault Sport">Renault Mégane RS</a>, which own the world records in their categories, such as the Nürburgring,<sup id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106">[106]</a></sup> and the Suzuka circuit and awards from <i><a href="/wiki/What_Car%3F" title="What Car?">What Car?</a></i>,<sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107">[107]</a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/Evo_(magazine)" title="Evo (magazine)">Evo</a></i>, and other magazines.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_sport_RS_01_-_2014_Paris_Motor_Show_01.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Renault_sport_RS_01_-_2014_Paris_Motor_Show_01.jpg/220px-Renault_sport_RS_01_-_2014_Paris_Motor_Show_01.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Renault_sport_RS_01_-_2014_Paris_Motor_Show_01.jpg/330px-Renault_sport_RS_01_-_2014_Paris_Motor_Show_01.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Renault_sport_RS_01_-_2014_Paris_Motor_Show_01.jpg/440px-Renault_sport_RS_01_-_2014_Paris_Motor_Show_01.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5472" data-file-height="3648" /></a>

</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Formula_One">Formula One</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Formula One">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Alonso_(Renault)_qualifying_at_USGP_2005.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Alonso_%28Renault%29_qualifying_at_USGP_2005.jpg/220px-Alonso_%28Renault%29_qualifying_at_USGP_2005.jpg" width="220" height="97" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Alonso_%28Renault%29_qualifying_at_USGP_2005.jpg/330px-Alonso_%28Renault%29_qualifying_at_USGP_2005.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Alonso_%28Renault%29_qualifying_at_USGP_2005.jpg/440px-Alonso_%28Renault%29_qualifying_at_USGP_2005.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1162" data-file-height="514" /></a>

<div class="thumbcaption">

Renault Megane RS III</div>
</div>
</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Renault_in_Formula_One" title="Renault in Formula One">Renault in Formula One</a></div>
<p>Renault introduced the <a href="/wiki/Turbocharger" title="Turbocharger">turbo</a> engine to Formula One when they debuted their first car, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_RS01" title="Renault RS01">Renault RS01</a> at <a href="/wiki/Silverstone_Circuit" title="Silverstone Circuit">Silverstone</a> in 1977. The Renault team continued until 1986. From 1989 Renault supplied engines to the successful <a href="/wiki/Williams-Renault" class="mw-redirect" title="Williams-Renault">Williams-Renault</a> car.</p>
<p>Renault took over the <a href="/wiki/Benetton_Formula" title="Benetton Formula">Benetton Formula</a> team in 2000<sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108">[108]</a></sup> for the <a href="/wiki/F1_2001" class="mw-redirect" title="F1 2001">2001</a> season and renamed it <a href="/wiki/Renault_F1" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault F1">Renault F1</a> in <a href="/wiki/F1_2002" class="mw-redirect" title="F1 2002">2002</a>. In <a href="/wiki/2005_Formula_One_season" title="2005 Formula One season">2005</a> and <a href="/wiki/2006_Formula_One_Season" class="mw-redirect" title="2006 Formula One Season">2006</a> the team won the Constructors' and Drivers' titles (with Fernando Alonso).<sup id="cite_ref-109" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109">[109]</a></sup> At the <a href="/wiki/2005_French_Grand_Prix" title="2005 French Grand Prix">2005 French Grand Prix</a> <a href="/wiki/Carlos_Ghosn" title="Carlos Ghosn">Carlos Ghosn</a> set out his policy regarding the company's involvement in motorsport:</p>
<dl>
<dd>"We are not in Formula One out of habit or tradition. We're here to show our talent and that we can do it properly&#160;... Formula One is a cost if you don't get the results. Formula One is an investment if you do have them and know how to exploit them."</dd>
</dl>
<p>Renault powered the winning 2010 <a href="/wiki/Red_Bull_Racing" title="Red Bull Racing">Red Bull Racing</a> team, and took a similar role with its old team in December 2010, when it sold its final stake to the investment group <a href="/wiki/Genii_Capital" title="Genii Capital">Genii Capital</a>, the main stakeholder<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-110">[110]</a></sup> since December 2009,<sup id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">[111]</a></sup> ending Renault's direct role in running a F1 team for the second time.<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112">[112]</a></sup> Renault returned to F1 as a works team for the 2016 season.<sup id="cite_ref-RSPRRSPC_7-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RSPRRSPC-7">[7]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-F1RTN_113-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-F1RTN-113">[113]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rallying">Rallying</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Rallying">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renault has been involved in <a href="/wiki/Rallying" title="Rallying">rallying</a> from an early era. Marcel Renault won the 1902 Rallye Paris-Vienna, but lost his life while competing in the 1903 Paris-Madrid rally.<sup id="cite_ref-RALL02_114-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL02-114">[114]</a></sup></p>
<p>During the 1950s and 1960s, Renault manufactured several small cars with <a href="/wiki/Rear_wheel_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Rear wheel drive">rear wheel drive</a> in some cases, as the <a href="/wiki/Renault_4CV" title="Renault 4CV">4CV</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_R8" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault R8">R8</a> or the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Dauphine" title="Renault Dauphine">Dauphine</a>. These cars were well-adapted to the rally of the time, and the tuner <a href="/wiki/Amedee_Gordini" class="mw-redirect" title="Amedee Gordini">Amedee Gordini</a> collaborated with its performance.<sup id="cite_ref-RALL02_114-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL02-114">[114]</a></sup> In the 1950s the Renault Dauphine won several international rallies, including the 1956 <a href="/wiki/Mille_Miglia" title="Mille Miglia">Mille Miglia</a> and the 1958 <a href="/wiki/Monte_Carlo_Rally" title="Monte Carlo Rally">Monte Carlo Rally</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-RALL01_115-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL01-115">[115]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1973, Renault took control of <a href="/wiki/Alpine_(car_maker)" class="mw-redirect" title="Alpine (car maker)">Automobiles Alpine</a>, a related company for several years, which was responsible for building successful rally cars such as the <a href="/wiki/Alpine_A110" title="Alpine A110">A110</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-RALL03_116-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL03-116">[116]</a></sup> A highly evolved A110 won the first <a href="/wiki/World_Rally_Championship" title="World Rally Championship">World Rally Championship</a>, representing Alpine-Renault.<sup id="cite_ref-RALL02_114-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL02-114">[114]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1976, the Alpine's competition department and the Gordini factory at Viry-Chatillon were merged into Renault Sport.<sup id="cite_ref-RALL03_116-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL03-116">[116]</a></sup> The focus shifted to Formula One, although Renault achieved several victories including the 1981 Monte Carlo Rally with the <a href="/wiki/Renault_5_Turbo" title="Renault 5 Turbo">Renault 5 Turbo</a><sup id="cite_ref-RALL01_115-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL01-115">[115]</a></sup> before retirement from the world rally in late 1994.<sup id="cite_ref-RALL02_114-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RALL02-114">[114]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault cars also participate of <a href="/wiki/Off-roading" title="Off-roading">cross-country</a> races, most prominently the <a href="/wiki/Dakar_Rally" title="Dakar Rally">Dakar Rally</a>. The Marreau brothers won the <a href="/wiki/1982_Paris%E2%80%93Dakar_Rally" title="1982 Paris–Dakar Rally">1982 edition</a> driving a <a href="/wiki/Renault_20" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 20">Renault 20</a> <a href="/wiki/Turbocharger" title="Turbocharger">Turbo</a> <a href="/wiki/Four-wheel_drive" title="Four-wheel drive">4x4</a> prototype.<sup id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117">[117]</a></sup></p>
<p>Later, Renault provided a Renault Megane platform<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2015)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> and sponsored the <a href="/wiki/Jean-Louis_Schlesser" title="Jean-Louis Schlesser">Schlesser</a>-Renault <a href="/wiki/Elf_Aquitaine" title="Elf Aquitaine">Elf</a> <a href="/wiki/Buggy_(automobile)" title="Buggy (automobile)">buggies</a> that won the 1999<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-118">[118]</a></sup> and 2000 editions.<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119">[119]</a></sup> The 1999 car was the first <a href="/wiki/Two-wheel_drive" title="Two-wheel drive">two-wheel drive</a> Dakar's winner.<sup id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-120">[120]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renaults won the <a href="/wiki/European_Rally_Championship" title="European Rally Championship">European Rally Championship</a> four times, in 1970, 1999, 2004 and 2005.<sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121">[121]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Corporate_governance">Corporate governance</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Corporate governance">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Renault's head office is in <a href="/wiki/Boulogne-Billancourt" title="Boulogne-Billancourt">Boulogne-Billancourt</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Boulogne_122-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Boulogne-122">[122]</a></sup> The head office is located near the old Renault factories; Renault has maintained a historical presence in Boulogne-Billancourt<sup id="cite_ref-123" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-123">[123]</a></sup> since the company's opening in 1898.<sup id="cite_ref-Boulogne_122-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Boulogne-122">[122]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault is administered through a Board of Directors, an Executive Committee and a Management Committee.<sup id="cite_ref-LEAD_124-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LEAD-124">[124]</a></sup> As of May 2014<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, members of the 19-seat board include Carlos Ghosn, <a href="/wiki/Alain_J._P._Belda" title="Alain J. P. Belda">Alain J. P. Belda</a>, <a href="/wiki/Charles_de_Croisset" title="Charles de Croisset">Charles de Croisset</a>, <a href="/wiki/Thierry_Desmarest" title="Thierry Desmarest">Thierry Desmarest</a>, <a href="/wiki/Yuriko_Koike" title="Yuriko Koike">Yuriko Koike</a>, <a href="/wiki/Marc_Ladreit_de_Lacharri%C3%A8re" title="Marc Ladreit de Lacharrière">Marc Ladreit de Lacharrière</a>, <a href="/wiki/Franck_Riboud" title="Franck Riboud">Franck Riboud</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pascale_Sourisse" title="Pascale Sourisse">Pascale Sourisse</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-125" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-125">[125]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Products_and_technologies">Products and technologies</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Products and technologies">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Concept_cars">Concept cars</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Concept cars">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Kangoo_Z.E._Concept.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Renault_Kangoo_Z.E._Concept.JPG/220px-Renault_Kangoo_Z.E._Concept.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Renault_Kangoo_Z.E._Concept.JPG/330px-Renault_Kangoo_Z.E._Concept.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Renault_Kangoo_Z.E._Concept.JPG/440px-Renault_Kangoo_Z.E._Concept.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1536" /></a>

</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Eolab_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_004.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Renault_Eolab_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_004.jpg/220px-Renault_Eolab_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_004.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Renault_Eolab_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_004.jpg/330px-Renault_Eolab_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_004.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Renault_Eolab_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_004.jpg/440px-Renault_Eolab_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_004.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5184" data-file-height="3456" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">

<a href="/wiki/Renault_Eolab" title="Renault Eolab">Renault Eolab</a>, a 1l/100km hybrid concept car</div>
</div>
</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Renault_vehicles#Concept_cars" title="List of Renault vehicles">List of Renault vehicles: Concept cars</a></div>
<p>Renault's concept cars show future design and technology directions. Since 2008 Renault has displayed various <a href="/wiki/All-electric_car" class="mw-redirect" title="All-electric car">all-electric car</a> <a href="/wiki/Concept_vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Concept vehicle">concepts</a> under the name <a href="/wiki/Renault_Z.E." title="Renault Z.E.">"Z.E."</a>, for <a href="/wiki/Zero_emission" title="Zero emission">zero emission</a>, starting with a concept based on the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Kangoo" title="Renault Kangoo">Renault Kangoo</a> Be Bop. Further concepts and announcements followed, with production of the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Fluence_Z.E." title="Renault Fluence Z.E.">Fluence Z.E.</a> saloon beginning in 2011 and the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Zoe" title="Renault Zoe">Renault Zoe</a> in 2012.</p>
<p>Renault revealed the Ondelios <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_vehicle" title="Hybrid electric vehicle">hybrid</a> concept in 2008.<sup id="cite_ref-127" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127">[127]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-128" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-128">[128]</a></sup> but this was overtaken by the Z.E. programme. However, Renault presented a new hybrid car in September 2014, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Eolab" title="Renault Eolab">Eolab</a>, which incorporates various innovations that the company said will be added to production models by 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-129" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-129">[129]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2014 at the New Delhi Auto Show, Renault announced a new model, the Kwid Concept, which comes with helicopter drone.<sup id="cite_ref-Gizmag1_130-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gizmag1-130">[130]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Electric_vehicle">Electric vehicle</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Electric vehicle">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/Renault%E2%80%93Nissan_Alliance#Zero-emission_vehicles" title="Renault–Nissan Alliance">Renault–Nissan Alliance zero-emission vehicles</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/66/Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG/220px-Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/66/Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG/330px-Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/66/Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG/440px-Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_Zoe_on_MIAS_2012.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Renault_Zoe" title="Renault Zoe">Renault Zoe</a>, a pure <a href="/wiki/Electric_car" title="Electric car">electric car</a> with a 210&#160;km to 230&#160;km range.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG/220px-Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG/330px-Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG/440px-Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG 2x" data-file-width="3000" data-file-height="2000" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Autolib_Paris_04_2016_7374.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Renault_Twizy" title="Renault Twizy">Renault Twizy</a> all-electric <a href="/wiki/Heavy_quadricycle" class="mw-redirect" title="Heavy quadricycle">heavy quadricycle</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 2013, Renault became the leader of electric vehicles sales in Europe, thanks to its large range of vehicles (Twizy, Zoe, Fluence, Kangoo).<sup id="cite_ref-131" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-131">[131]</a></sup></p>
<p>Beginning in 2008, Renault made agreements for its planned zero-emissions products, including with Israel, Portugal, Denmark and the US states of Tennessee and Oregon,<sup id="cite_ref-automotivedesign-europe.com_132-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-automotivedesign-europe.com-132">[132]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Yokohama" title="Yokohama">Yokohama</a> in Japan and the Principality of Monaco.<sup id="cite_ref-133" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-133">[133]</a></sup> Serge Yoccoz is the electric vehicle project director.<sup id="cite_ref-134" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134">[134]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2008, Renault-Nissan signed a deal to produce electric cars for an initiative in Israel with <a href="/wiki/Better_Place" title="Better Place">Better Place</a>, a US company developing new non-petroleum–based transport infrastructure. Renault aimed to sell 10–20,000 cars a year in Israel.<sup id="cite_ref-reuters_develop_Israel_135-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reuters_develop_Israel-135">[135]</a></sup> Renault also agreed to develop exchangeable batteries for the project.<sup id="cite_ref-136" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136">[136]</a></sup> Renault collaborated with Better Place to produce a network of <a href="/wiki/All-electric_vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="All-electric vehicle">all-electric vehicles</a> and thousands of <a href="/wiki/Charging_station" title="Charging station">charging stations</a> in Denmark, planned to be operational by 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-137" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-137">[137]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Renault_Fluence_Z.E." title="Renault Fluence Z.E.">Renault Fluence Z.E.</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-138">[138]</a></sup> was selected for the Israel project. It became the first zero-emission vehicle with a switchable battery,<sup id="cite_ref-israel21c_139-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-israel21c-139">[139]</a></sup> with trials in 2010 undertaken with the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Laguna" title="Renault Laguna">Renault Laguna</a>. Renault ended the partnership in 2013, following Better Place's bankruptcy, with only 1000 vehicle sales in Israel and 240 in Denmark.<sup id="cite_ref-140" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140">[140]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault-Nissan and the largest French electric utility, <a href="/wiki/Electricite_de_France" class="mw-redirect" title="Electricite de France">Electricite de France</a> (EDF) signed an agreement to promote electric vehicles in France. The partnership planned to pilot projects on battery management and charging infrastructure.<sup id="cite_ref-141" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-141">[141]</a></sup> Renault-Nissan also signed deals with Ireland's <a href="/wiki/ESB_Group" title="ESB Group">ESB</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-142">[142]</a></sup> and in <a href="/wiki/Milton_Keynes" title="Milton Keynes">Milton Keynes</a> as part of the UK's Plugged in Places national project.<sup id="cite_ref-143" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-143">[143]</a></sup></p>
<table class="cquote" role="presentation" style="margin:auto; border-collapse: collapse; border: none; background-color: transparent; width: auto;">
<tr>
<td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: top; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: left; padding: 10px 10px;">“</td>
<td style="vertical-align: top; border: none; padding: 4px 10px;">We have decided to introduce zero-emission vehicles as quickly as possible in order to ensure individual mobility against the background of high oil prices and better environmental protection</td>
<td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: bottom; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: right; padding: 10px 10px;">”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="3" class="cquotecite" style="border: none; padding-right: 4%; font-size: smaller; text-align: right;"><cite>— Carlos Ghosn, CEO of Renault and Nissan<sup id="cite_ref-automotivedesign-europe.com_132-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-automotivedesign-europe.com-132">[132]</a></sup></cite></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>According to <a href="/wiki/Carlos_Ghosn" title="Carlos Ghosn">Ghosn</a>, the Renault-Nissan alliance was a fundamental step in <a href="/wiki/Electric_car" title="Electric car">electric car</a> development, and that they needed each other for other issues such as battery manufacturing, <a href="/wiki/Electric_vehicle_infrastructure" class="mw-redirect" title="Electric vehicle infrastructure">charging infrastructure</a> and business strategy.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog1_144-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog1-144">[144]</a></sup></p>
<table class="cquote" role="presentation" style="margin:auto; border-collapse: collapse; border: none; background-color: transparent; width: auto;">
<tr>
<td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: top; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: left; padding: 10px 10px;">“</td>
<td style="vertical-align: top; border: none; padding: 4px 10px;">I don't think either Renault or Nissan would have been able to launch an EV alone successfully. You can have an electric car alone. But what you cannot have is an EV business system, from batteries to recycling to cars to infrastructure to negotiation, by being alone.</td>
<td style="width: 20px; vertical-align: bottom; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: right; padding: 10px 10px;">”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="3" class="cquotecite" style="border: none; padding-right: 4%; font-size: smaller; text-align: right;"><cite>— Carlos Ghosn, CEO of Renault and Nissan<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog1_144-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog1-144">[144]</a></sup></cite></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The Renault-Nissan group is a member of the <a href="/wiki/PHEV_Research_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="PHEV Research Center">PHEV Research Center</a>.</p>
<p>In September 2013, Renault and <a href="/wiki/Bollor%C3%A9" title="Bolloré">Bolloré</a> announced an agreement to collaborate on a new electric vehicle and in car-sharing project.<sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145">[145]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Renault Zoe, with 18,453 registrations, was the top selling all-<a href="/wiki/Electric_car" title="Electric car">electric car</a> in Europe in 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-146" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-146">[146]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-147" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-147">[147]</a></sup> With 11,873 units sold during the first half of 2016, the Zoe continued to rank as the top selling <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_electric_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Plug-in electric car">plug-in electric car</a> in Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-Zoe50K_148-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Zoe50K-148">[148]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149">[149]</a></sup> Global Zoe sales achieved the 50,000 unit milestone in June 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-Zoe50K_148-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Zoe50K-148">[148]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Groupe_Renault" class="mw-redirect" title="Groupe Renault">Groupe Renault</a> global electric vehicle sales passed the 100,000 unit milestone in September 2016, with <a href="/wiki/Renault_Zoe" title="Renault Zoe">Zoe</a> sales representing 54%, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Kangoo_Z.E." class="mw-redirect" title="Renault Kangoo Z.E.">Kangoo Z.E.</a> with 24%, the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Twizy" title="Renault Twizy">Twizy</a> with 18% and the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Fluence_Z.E." title="Renault Fluence Z.E.">Fluence Z.E.</a> and its Korean rebadged <a href="/wiki/Samsung_SM3_Z.E." class="mw-redirect" title="Samsung SM3 Z.E.">Samsung SM3 Z.E.</a> together representing 4%.<sup id="cite_ref-RN350K_150-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RN350K-150">[150]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-151" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151">[151]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Eco.C2.B2">Eco²</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Eco²">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In 2007 Renault introduced a new line of eco-friendly derivatives marked eco² that were based on production platforms. A minimum of 5% recycled plastic was used and the vehicle's materials were 95% reusable. Eco²'s CO<sup>2</sup> emissions were not to exceed 140g/km, or would be <a href="/wiki/Biofuel" title="Biofuel">biofuel</a> compatible.<sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152">[152]</a></sup> At the 2008 Fleet World Honours, Renault received the Environment Award. The chairman of Judges, George Emmerson, commented, "This was the most hotly contested category in the history of the Fleet World Honours, such is the clamour for organizations' green credentials to be recognised. There were some very impressive entries, but the panel felt that Renault's impressive range of low-emission vehicles was the most tangible, and the most quantifiable.<sup id="cite_ref-153" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-153">[153]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="R-Link">R-Link</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: R-Link">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<table class="plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Primary_sources" role="presentation">

<td class="mbox-image">

<td class="mbox-text"><span class="mbox-text-span">This section with source from EC <b>may rely excessively on sources too closely associated with the subject</b>, potentially preventing the article from being <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verifiable</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view" title="Wikipedia:Neutral point of view">neutral</a>. <span class="hide-when-compact">Please help <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit">improve it</a> by replacing them with more appropriate <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" title="Wikipedia:Citing sources">citations</a> to <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Independent_sources" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Independent sources">reliable, independent, third-party sources</a>.</span> <small><i>(March 2015)</i></small> <small class="hide-when-compact"><i>(<a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small></span></td>

</table>
<p>The R-Link infotainment system, developed by Renault and the <a href="/wiki/Centre_commun_d%27%C3%A9tudes_de_t%C3%A9l%C3%A9vision_et_t%C3%A9l%C3%A9communications" title="Centre commun d'études de télévision et télécommunications">CCETT</a> labs during the 1980s,<sup id="cite_ref-Carminat_Renault_system_100-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Carminat_Renault_system-100">[100]</a></sup> produced with <a href="/wiki/TomTom" title="TomTom">TomTom</a> and fitted in Renault's vehicles, was ranked first in a user accessibility study performed by an independent consulting British company SBD in Europe, R-Link getting 85% of the users satisfaction, whereas the second "big five" automotive maker got a 10% lower satisfaction from the users.<sup id="cite_ref-R-Link_best_infotainment_154-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-R-Link_best_infotainment-154">[154]</a></sup>&#160;<b>·</b> <sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">[155]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources" title="Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources"><span title="&quot;The">unreliable source?</span></a></i>]</sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Writing_better_articles#Stay_on_topic" title="Wikipedia:Writing better articles"><span title="The material near this tag may contain information that is not relevant to the article's main topic. (March 2015)">relevant?</span></a> <span class="metadata">– <a href="/wiki/Talk:Renault" title="Talk:Renault">discuss</a></span></i>]</sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Autonomous_vehicles">Autonomous vehicles</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Autonomous vehicles">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renault plans to introduce <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Autonomous vehicle">autonomous vehicle</a> technology by 2020. The company unveiled a prototype, the Next Two (based on the Zoe), in February 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">[156]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Vehicle_design">Vehicle design</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Vehicle design">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Design">Design</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Design">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="The_.22pre-design.22_era">The "pre-design" era</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: The &quot;pre-design&quot; era">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>During its early years, Renault only manufactured the cars' chassis, while the bodywork was in charge of coachbuilders. The first car with Renault's bodywork was the "Taxi de la Marne" introduced in 1905.<sup id="cite_ref-D1_157-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D1-157">[157]</a></sup> Most Renault-made bodyworks were simple and utilitarian until the Reinastella unveiling in 1928. In the 1930s, Renault developed streamlined cars as the Viva Grand Sport. In the 1950s the company worked with <a href="/wiki/Carrozzeria_Ghia" title="Carrozzeria Ghia">Ghia</a> designers.<sup id="cite_ref-DMD_158-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DMD-158">[158]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_Styling">Renault Styling</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Renault Styling">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In 1961, with the assistance of the independent designer <a href="/wiki/Philippe_Charbonneaux" title="Philippe Charbonneaux">Philippe Charbonneaux</a> (responsible for the R8), the company created Renault Styling as a design department, led by <a href="/wiki/Gaston_Juchet" title="Gaston Juchet">Gaston Juchet</a> since 1963.<sup id="cite_ref-DMD_158-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DMD-158">[158]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-GC_159-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GC-159">[159]</a></sup> In 1975, <a href="/wiki/Robert_Opron" title="Robert Opron">Robert Opron</a> was named chief designer<sup id="cite_ref-GC_159-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GC-159">[159]</a></sup> and Renault Styling was divided into Interior, Exterior and Advanced Design groups.<sup id="cite_ref-D1_157-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D1-157">[157]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the 1960s an in-house <a href="/wiki/Computer-aided_design" title="Computer-aided design">CAD</a> <a href="/wiki/Computer-aided_manufacturing" title="Computer-aided manufacturing">CAM</a> system called <a href="/wiki/UNISURF" title="UNISURF">UNISURF</a> was introduced, led by <a href="/wiki/Pierre_B%C3%A9zier" title="Pierre Bézier">Pierre Bézier</a> (who popularised <a href="/wiki/B%C3%A9zier_curve" title="Bézier curve">Bézier curves</a> and worked at Renault from 1933 to 1975.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Industrial_Design_Department">Industrial Design Department</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Industrial Design Department">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In 1987, Renault named <a href="/wiki/Patrick_le_Qu%C3%A9ment" class="mw-redirect" title="Patrick le Quément">Patrick le Quément</a> as chief designer<sup id="cite_ref-D2_160-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D2-160">[160]</a></sup> and created the Industrial Design Department to replace Renault Styling. The new division incorporated a new management system, with more technology and personnel. Renault gave it the same importance as Engineering and Product Planning, participating in product development.<sup id="cite_ref-D1_157-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D1-157">[157]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-GC_159-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GC-159">[159]</a></sup></p>
<p>Le Quément was responsible for bold designs such as the Mégane II and the Vel Satis,<sup id="cite_ref-161" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-161">[161]</a></sup> giving Renault a more coherent and stylish image.<sup id="cite_ref-162" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-162">[162]</a></sup> In 1995, Design and Quality were merged under le Quément's direction.<sup id="cite_ref-D1_157-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D1-157">[157]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-D2_160-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D2-160">[160]</a></sup> Later, the new department moved to Guyancourt's Technocentre, which also became the base for Engineering and Product Planning. the group was organized in three sections: Automobile Design; Truck, LCV and Bus Design; and Concept Cars and Advanced Design. During the next years satellite centres opened in Spain (1999), Paris (2000), South Korea (2003), Romania (2007), India (2007)<sup id="cite_ref-D1_157-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D1-157">[157]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-GC_159-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GC-159">[159]</a></sup> and Brazil (2008).<sup id="cite_ref-163" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-163">[163]</a></sup></p>
<p>At the end of 2009, le Quément was replaced by <a href="/wiki/Laurens_van_den_Acker" title="Laurens van den Acker">Laurens van den Acker</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-D2_160-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-D2-160">[160]</a></sup> who introduced the "cycle of life" concept to Renault's design.<sup id="cite_ref-164" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164">[164]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Engineering_and_Product_Planning">Engineering and Product Planning</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Engineering and Product Planning">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg/220px-Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg/330px-Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg/440px-Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5184" data-file-height="3456" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_moteur_energy_dCi_160_twin_turbo_EDC_-_Mondial_de_l%27Automobile_de_Paris_2014_-_001.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Renault <a href="/wiki/Twin-turbo" title="Twin-turbo">twin-turbo</a> engine</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Most of Renault engineering was decentralised until 1998, when the Technocentre became the main Renault's engineering facility.<sup id="cite_ref-R1985_64-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-R1985-64">[64]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-TECHNO_165-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TECHNO-165">[165]</a></sup> Satellite centres exist, including Renault Technologies Americas (with branches in Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia and Mexico), Renault Technologies Romania (branches in Morocco, Russia, Slovenia and Turkey) and Renault Technologies Spain (branch in Portugal).<sup id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-166">[166]</a></sup> As of 2013<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, Renault's engineering section had over 6500 employees worldwide, of which 34% were engineers and 63% technicians.<sup id="cite_ref-167" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-167">[167]</a></sup> Engine development is in charge of a specific division, Renault Powertrains, with nearly 65 engineers.<sup id="cite_ref-168" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-168">[168]</a></sup> Overseas engineering is increasing and R&amp;D teams are in charge of adjusting existing vehicles to local needs and budgets.<sup id="cite_ref-169" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-169">[169]</a></sup></p>
<p>As of 2014<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup> Engineering and Product Planning are directed by Gaspar Gascon Abellan<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-170">[170]</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Philippe_Klein" title="Philippe Klein">Philippe Klein</a><sup id="cite_ref-171" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171">[171]</a></sup> respectively.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Technocentre">Technocentre</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Technocentre">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG/220px-La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG/330px-La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG/440px-La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:La_Ruche_du_technocentre_vue_depuis_les_Gogottes.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
View of the Technocentre from the Jardin des Gogottes</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The Renault Technocentre (<small>French pronunciation:&#160;​</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_French" title="Help:IPA for French">[ʁəno tɛknɔˈsɑ̃tʁ]</a></span>)) is the main research and development facility. It is located in Guyancourt. It covers 150 hectares<sup id="cite_ref-172" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-172">[172]</a></sup> and integrates all departments involved in developing products and industrial processes (design, engineering and product planning) as well as supplier representatives. The Technocentre gathers more than 8000 employees<sup id="cite_ref-173" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-173">[173]</a></sup> and comprises three main sections, The Advance Precinct, The Hive and the prototype build centre. The Advance Precinct, a stepped structure surrounded by a lake, has design studios and other departments related to early design stages. The Hive is the tallest structure and includes research and engineering facilities dedicated to the development process of new vehicles. The prototype build centre is an extension of The Hive. The three main structures are accompanied by smaller technical buildings.<sup id="cite_ref-TECHNO_165-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TECHNO-165">[165]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Technocentre was one of the first enterprises to have real-time life-size 3D modelling systems.<sup id="cite_ref-174" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-174">[174]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_Tech">Renault Tech</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Renault Tech">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renault Tech is a division of <a href="/wiki/Renault_Sport" title="Renault Sport">Renault Sport Technologies</a>, headquartered in Les Ulis. It was established in 2008 and is in charge of modifying cars and vans for special purposes (transporting people with reduced mobility, driving school cars, business fleets).<sup id="cite_ref-175" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-175">[175]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-176" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-176">[176]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Subsidiaries_and_alliances">Subsidiaries and alliances</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Subsidiaries and alliances">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_offices_in_Madrid_(Spain)_03.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Renault_offices_in_Madrid_%28Spain%29_03.jpg/220px-Renault_offices_in_Madrid_%28Spain%29_03.jpg" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Renault_offices_in_Madrid_%28Spain%29_03.jpg/330px-Renault_offices_in_Madrid_%28Spain%29_03.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Renault_offices_in_Madrid_%28Spain%29_03.jpg/440px-Renault_offices_in_Madrid_%28Spain%29_03.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2866" data-file-height="1900" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Renault_offices_in_Madrid_(Spain)_03.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<i><a href="/wiki/Renault_Espa%C3%B1a" title="Renault España">Renault España</a></i> offices in <a href="/wiki/Madrid" title="Madrid">Madrid</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault-Nissan">Renault-Nissan</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: Renault-Nissan">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Renault-Nissan_Alliance" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault-Nissan Alliance">Renault-Nissan Alliance</a></div>
<p>Renault has a 43.4% stake in Nissan, and Nissan holds a 15% stake (with no voting rights) in Renault, thereby giving it effective control. Renault has a 50% stake in the joint venture Renault-Nissan b.v., which was established to manage the Renault-Nissan alliance. The company is responsible for the management of two joint companies, RNPO (Renault Nissan Purchasing Organization) and RNIS (Renault-Nissan Information Services).<sup id="cite_ref-177" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-177">[177]</a></sup> Combined vehicle sales in 2008 reached 6.9&#160;million (including AvtoVAZ), making the Renault-Nissan Alliance the world's third-largest automotive group.<sup id="cite_ref-178" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-178">[178]</a></sup></p>
<p>As well as sharing engines and joint-development of zero-emissions technology, Nissan increased its presence in Europe by badging various Renault van models such as the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Kangoo" title="Renault Kangoo">Renault Kangoo</a>/<a href="/wiki/Nissan_Kubistar" class="mw-redirect" title="Nissan Kubistar">Nissan Kubistar</a>, <a href="/wiki/Renault_Master" title="Renault Master">Renault Master</a>/<a href="/wiki/Nissan_Interstar" class="mw-redirect" title="Nissan Interstar">Nissan Interstar</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Trafic" title="Renault Trafic">Renault Trafic</a>/<a href="/wiki/Nissan_Primastar" class="mw-redirect" title="Nissan Primastar">Nissan Primastar</a>. Some passenger cars have also been badged-engineered, such as the Renault Clio-based <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Platina" class="mw-redirect" title="Nissan Platina">Nissan Platina</a> in Brazil. The "Renault Production System" standard used by all Renault factories borrowed extensively from the "Nissan Production Way" and resulted in Renault productivity improving by 15%. The alliance led to the loss of 21,000 jobs, the closure of three assembly and two powertrain plants.<sup id="cite_ref-179" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-179">[179]</a></sup></p>
<p>In March 2010 the Renault-Nissan alliance opened its first joint facility in <a href="/wiki/Chennai" title="Chennai">Chennai</a>, India, investing 45&#160;billion rupees (US$991.1&#160;million).<sup id="cite_ref-180" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-180">[180]</a></sup> The facility builds the <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Micra" title="Nissan Micra">Nissan Micra</a>. The Renault Fluence and <a href="/wiki/Renault_Koleos" title="Renault Koleos">Renault Koleos</a> are intended to be assembled there from <a href="/wiki/Knock-down_kit" title="Knock-down kit">completely knocked-down units</a>. As a result of opening its own factory, Renault ended its five-year <a href="/wiki/Mahindra_Renault_Limited" title="Mahindra Renault Limited">Mahindra Renault</a> joint venture with <a href="/wiki/Mahindra_%26_Mahindra" title="Mahindra &amp; Mahindra">Mahindra &amp; Mahindra</a> company to make and sell the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Logan" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault Logan">Renault Logan</a> in India.<sup id="cite_ref-181" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-181">[181]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault-Nissan_and_Daimler_alliance">Renault-Nissan and Daimler alliance</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Renault-Nissan and Daimler alliance">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 7 April 2010 Ghosn and <a href="/wiki/Daimler_AG" title="Daimler AG">Daimler AG</a> CEO <a href="/wiki/Dieter_Zetsche" title="Dieter Zetsche">Dieter Zetsche</a> announced a partnership between the three companies.<sup id="cite_ref-182" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-182">[182]</a></sup> Daimler acquired a 3.1 per cent stake in Renault-Nissan and Renault and Nissan each took a 1.55 per cent stake in Daimler.<sup id="cite_ref-183" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-183">[183]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dacia">Dacia</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Dacia">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Automobile_Dacia" title="Automobile Dacia">Automobile Dacia</a></div>
<p>In 1999, Renault acquired a 51% controlling stake from the Romanian-based manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Automobile_Dacia" title="Automobile Dacia">Automobile Dacia</a>, which increased to 99.43%.<sup id="cite_ref-184" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-184">[184]</a></sup> As part of the Renault group, Dacia is a regional marque of entry-levels cars focused on Europe and Northern Africa which shares various models with the Renault marque.<sup id="cite_ref-AUTONEWS_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AUTONEWS-13">[13]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_Samsung_Motors">Renault Samsung Motors</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Renault Samsung Motors">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Renault_Samsung_Motors" title="Renault Samsung Motors">Renault Samsung Motors</a></div>
<p>Renault acquired the car division of Samsung on 1 September 2000 in a $560 million deal for 70% of the company,<sup id="cite_ref-185" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-185">[185]</a></sup> eventually rising its stake to 80.1%.<sup id="cite_ref-186" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-186">[186]</a></sup> Renault Samsung Motors is a marque used almost exclusively in South Korea (although some models are sold in Chile). The majority of the company's production at its Busan plant is exported under the Renault badge.<sup id="cite_ref-187" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-187">[187]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="AvtoVAZ">AvtoVAZ</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: AvtoVAZ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/AvtoVAZ" title="AvtoVAZ">AvtoVAZ</a></div>
<p>In February 2008 Renault acquired a 25% share in <a href="/wiki/AvtoVAZ" title="AvtoVAZ">AvtoVAZ</a>, known for its <a href="/wiki/Lada" title="Lada">Lada</a> range of vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-188" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-188">[188]</a></sup> VAZ had been seeking a strategic partner since the late nineties. Its owners had little success in forming an alliance with various firms.</p>
<p>Renault began off and on in talks with AvtoVAZ in 2005, initially insisting that <a href="/wiki/Complete_knock_down" class="mw-redirect" title="Complete knock down">CKD</a> assemble Logans at its facilities, while VAZ intended to keep its own <a href="/wiki/Lada" title="Lada">Lada</a> brand and sought only a new platform and engine. After several rounds of talks, interrupted by VAZ's attempts to ally with <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat</a> and <a href="/wiki/Magna_International" title="Magna International">Magna</a>, Renault agreed to the partnership under terms similar to its Nissan deal. Renault and <a href="/wiki/Rosoboronexport" title="Rosoboronexport">Rosoboronexport</a>, the state corporation that is a major stockholder of VAZ, discussed Renault increasing its stake in VAZ to 50%.<sup id="cite_ref-189" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-189">[189]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="American_Motors">American Motors</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=35" title="Edit section: American Motors">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In 1979, Renault entered into an agreement with <a href="/wiki/American_Motors_Corporation" class="mw-redirect" title="American Motors Corporation">American Motors Corporation</a> (AMC) to sell cars in the US.<sup id="cite_ref-190" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-190">[190]</a></sup> A year later, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in AMC.<sup id="cite_ref-accent_191-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-accent-191">[191]</a></sup> This was not the first time the two companies had worked together. In the early 1960s, Renault assembled <a href="/wiki/Complete_knock_down" class="mw-redirect" title="Complete knock down">CKD</a> kits and marketed Ramblers in France.<sup id="cite_ref-192" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-192">[192]</a></sup> In 1982, Renault increased its stake in AMC to 46.4%.<sup id="cite_ref-193" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-193">[193]</a></sup> The Renault Alliance/Encore (a modified version of the Renault 9 and 11) entered production in the US, but following AMC's continued decline, Renault withdrew from the US in 1987 and sold its share to Chrysler.<sup id="cite_ref-194" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-194">[194]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="RCI_Banque">RCI Banque</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=36" title="Edit section: RCI Banque">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/RCI_Banque" title="RCI Banque">RCI Banque</a></div>
<p>RCI Banque is a wholly owned subsidiary that provides financial services for Renault marques worldwide and Nissan marques in Europe, Russia and South America.<sup id="cite_ref-195" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-195">[195]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-196" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-196">[196]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_Retail_Group">Renault Retail Group</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=37" title="Edit section: Renault Retail Group">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renault Retail Group is Renault's wholly owned automobile distributor for Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-A1_197-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A1-197">[197]</a></sup> In 1997, the French branches were merged to establish the subsidiary Renault France Automobiles (RFA). In 2001, it served as the basis for Renault Europe Automobiles (REA), which managed sales in Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-198" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-198">[198]</a></sup> In 2008, the company adopted its current name.<sup id="cite_ref-199" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-199">[199]</a></sup> Renault Retail Group operates in France, Austria, Belgium, the Czech Republic, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Poland, Portugal, Spain, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.<sup id="cite_ref-A1_197-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A1-197">[197]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Manufacturing_subsidiaries">Manufacturing subsidiaries</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=38" title="Edit section: Manufacturing subsidiaries">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
