<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Proposed_alliances">Proposed alliances</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=41" title="Edit section: Proposed alliances">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>On 30 June 2006, the media reported that General Motors convened an emergency board meeting to discuss a proposal by shareholder <a href="/wiki/Kirk_Kerkorian" title="Kirk Kerkorian">Kirk Kerkorian</a> to form an alliance with Renault-<a href="/wiki/Nissan_Motor_Co.,_Ltd." class="mw-redirect" title="Nissan Motor Co., Ltd.">Nissan</a>. However, GM CEO <a href="/wiki/Rick_Wagoner" title="Rick Wagoner">Richard Wagoner</a> felt that an alliance would disproportionaely benefit Renault's shareholders and that GM should receive compensation accordingly. Talks between GM and Renault ended on 4 October 2006.<sup id="cite_ref-213" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-213">[213]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2007, Renault-Nissan entered talks with Indian manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Bajaj_Auto" title="Bajaj Auto">Bajaj Auto</a> to develop a new ultra-low-cost car along the lines of the <a href="/wiki/Tata_Nano" title="Tata Nano">Tata Nano</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-214" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-214">[214]</a></sup> Renault's existing partner in India, Mahindra, was not interested in the project. The proposed joint venture did not come to fruition and in late 2009 they companies announced that Bajaj would develop and manufacturer the vehicle and supply Renault-Nissan with completed cars.<sup id="cite_ref-215" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-215">[215]</a></sup></p>
<p>On 7 October 2008 a Renault executive said the company was interested in acquiring or partnering with Chrysler.<sup id="cite_ref-216" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-216">[216]</a></sup> On 11 October 2008, the New York Times reported that <a href="/wiki/General_Motors" title="General Motors">General Motors</a>, Nissan and Renault had all been in discussions over the past month with Chrysler's owner <a href="/wiki/Cerberus_Capital_Management" title="Cerberus Capital Management">Cerberus Capital Management</a> about acquiring Chrysler.<sup id="cite_ref-217" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-217">[217]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="United_Kingdom">United Kingdom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=42" title="Edit section: United Kingdom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In 2014, two Renault models were among the most numerous on British roads: the Clio (ranked 6th by total number) and the Mégane (ranked 10th).<sup id="cite_ref-218" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-218">[218]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:The_Spectrum_Building,_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/The_Spectrum_Building%2C_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg/220px-The_Spectrum_Building%2C_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/The_Spectrum_Building%2C_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg/330px-The_Spectrum_Building%2C_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/The_Spectrum_Building%2C_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg/440px-The_Spectrum_Building%2C_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg 2x" data-file-width="480" data-file-height="640" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:The_Spectrum_Building,_West_Swindon_-_geograph.org.uk_-_287906.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The Renault Centre, ordered by Renault to <a href="/wiki/Norman_Foster" class="mw-redirect" title="Norman Foster">Norman Foster</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1970s.2C_1980s.2C_1990s">1970s, 1980s, 1990s</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=43" title="Edit section: 1970s, 1980s, 1990s">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The first Renaults to sustain sales in the UK were the Renault 5 and Renault 18, both of which attained six-digit sales figures during the late 1970s and early 1980s.</p>
<p>In 1980, Renault commissioned British architect <a href="/wiki/Norman_Foster" class="mw-redirect" title="Norman Foster">Norman Foster</a>, to build the <a href="/wiki/Renault_Centre" title="Renault Centre">Renault Centre</a>, an award-winning<sup id="cite_ref-219" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-219">[219]</a></sup> office and distribution centre in Swindon. It was easily identified by the extensive use of the corporate Renault yellow.</p>
<p>Renault enjoyed greater popularity with the arrival of the Clio supermini in March 1991. It was regularly among the best sellers during the 1990s. The successor (launched in 1998, alongside the final instalment of the successful "<a href="/wiki/Papa_%26_Nicole" title="Papa &amp; Nicole">Papa &amp; Nicole</a>" advertising campaign),<sup id="cite_ref-220" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-220">[220]</a></sup> continued its success. The sedan/saloon version, Thalia, was not launched in the United Kingdom.</p>
<p>Renault introduced the Mégane in April 1996 to steady sales, although it failed to reach the top ten during the first two years. In 1998, however, sales grew, making it Britain's sixth-best selling car and the second most popular in its sector.<sup id="cite_ref-221" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-221">[221]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2000s">2000s</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=44" title="Edit section: 2000s">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In 2006 Renault was Britain's third most popular brand, surpassed only by <a href="/wiki/Ford_of_Europe" title="Ford of Europe">Ford</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vauxhall_Motors" title="Vauxhall Motors">Vauxhall</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Renault_popular_in_UK_2006_222-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Renault_popular_in_UK_2006-222">[222]</a></sup></p>
<p>In November 2007, Renault UK lost a US$2&#160;million lawsuit against an independent distributor, who had placed orders for 217 cars under a discount scheme. This was intended for members of the British Airline Pilots Association. Three were legitimate, because they had "made a profit of some sort on every vehicle". Two Renault employees were criticised, for having "turned a blind eye" to the very large number of orders.<sup id="cite_ref-theregister.co.uk_223-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-theregister.co.uk-223">[223]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2008 Renault sales started declining, and the marque fell to the eighth most popular, with 89,570 sales (down 29% compared to 2007)<sup id="cite_ref-224" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-224">[224]</a></sup> and considerably less than 2002's 194,685 sales.<sup id="cite_ref-225" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-225">[225]</a></sup> Renault suffered more than most main brands during 2009, as the <a href="/wiki/Late_2000s_recession" class="mw-redirect" title="Late 2000s recession">recession</a> deepened and ended the year with 63,174 sales, and a reduced 3.17% market share.</p>
<p>During 2010, however, as the economy returned to growth, Renault sold more than 95,000 cars and increased its market share to 4.71%,<sup id="cite_ref-226" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-226">[226]</a></sup> before falling again in 2011 to 68,449, yielding a 3.53 per cent market share.<sup id="cite_ref-227" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-227">[227]</a></sup> In December 2011, Renault announced that the Laguna, Espace, Kangoo, Modus, and Wind lines would be discontinued as a cost-cutting measure, while 55 of its 190 British dealerships would close.<sup id="cite_ref-228" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-228">[228]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-229" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-229">[229]</a></sup> By 2014 Renault sales outperformed the market overall growth with a 41.9% increase,<sup id="cite_ref-230" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-230">[230]</a></sup> in spite of a range limited to the Clio, Captur, Mégane, Zoe, Scénic, Kangoo, Twizy and the third-generation Twingo, launched at the end of 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-231" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-231">[231]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Awards">Awards</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=45" title="Edit section: Awards">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Renault models have won the <i><a href="/wiki/European_Car_of_the_Year" title="European Car of the Year">European Car of the Year</a></i> award six times in the last forty years:</p>
<ul>
<li>1966: <a href="/wiki/Renault_16" title="Renault 16">Renault 16</a><sup id="cite_ref-232" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-232">[232]</a></sup></li>
<li>1982: <a href="/wiki/Renault_9" class="mw-redirect" title="Renault 9">Renault 9</a><sup id="cite_ref-233" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-233">[233]</a></sup></li>
<li>1991: <a href="/wiki/Renault_Clio" title="Renault Clio">Renault Clio</a><sup id="cite_ref-234" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-234">[234]</a></sup></li>
<li>1997: <a href="/wiki/Renault_Sc%C3%A9nic" title="Renault Scénic">Renault Scénic</a><sup id="cite_ref-235" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-235">[235]</a></sup></li>
<li>2003: <a href="/wiki/Renault_M%C3%A9gane" title="Renault Mégane">Renault Mégane</a> II<sup id="cite_ref-236" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-236">[236]</a></sup></li>
<li>2006: <a href="/wiki/Renault_Clio" title="Renault Clio">Renault Clio III</a><sup id="cite_ref-237" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-237">[237]</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Renault cars have won numerous national-level awards in Spain, Australia, Ireland, the United States,<sup id="cite_ref-Renault_car_of_the_year_USA_59-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Renault_car_of_the_year_USA-59">[59]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-238" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-238">[238]</a></sup> Denmark, and elsewhere. Renault and its Dacia subsidiary have won three "Autobest" car of the year awards for the Duster, Logan, and Symbol models.<sup id="cite_ref-239" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-239">[239]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Marketing_and_branding">Marketing and branding</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=46" title="Edit section: Marketing and branding">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_badge">Renault badge</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=47" title="Edit section: Renault badge">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renault's first badge was introduced in 1900 and consisted in the Renault brothers' intertwined initials. When the company started mass production in 1906, it adopted a gear-shaped logo with a car inside it. After World War I the company used a logo depicting an FT tank. In 1923 it introduced a new circle-shaped badge, which was replaced by the "diamond" or lozenge in 1925.<sup id="cite_ref-Dinesh_240-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dinesh-240">[240]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Lozenge" title="Lozenge">lozenge</a> of Renault means a diamond that expresses the brand's firm desire to project a strong and consistent corporate image.<sup id="cite_ref-EDM_241-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EDM-241">[241]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Renault diamond logo has been through many iterations.<sup id="cite_ref-Dinesh_240-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dinesh-240">[240]</a></sup> To modernise its image, Renault asked <a href="/wiki/Victor_Vasarely" title="Victor Vasarely">Victor Vasarely</a> to design its new logo in 1972. The transformed logo maintained the diamond shape. The design was later revised to reflect the more rounded lines of the brand's new styling cues.<sup id="cite_ref-Renault.com_242-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Renault.com-242">[242]</a></sup> The current badge has been in use since 1992.</p>
<p>The logo for web and print use was updated three times thereafter. In 2004 a more realistic representation inside a yellow square with the word "Renault" in <i>Renault Identité</i> typeface besides it was incorporated. In 2007, Saguez &amp; Partners produced a version with the word "Renault" inside the yellow square.<sup id="cite_ref-Dinesh_240-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dinesh-240">[240]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-243" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-243">[243]</a></sup></p>
<p>In April 2015, Renault introduced new designs to differentiate the company from the product brand, as part of the 'Passion for life' campaign. The new brand logo replaced the yellow background with a yellow stripe. A new typeface was also introduced. A corporate logo was unveiled at the 2015 Annual General Meeting, incorporating Renault, Dacia and Renault Samsung Motors.<sup id="cite_ref-244" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-244">[244]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-245" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-245">[245]</a></sup></p>
<p>The yellow associated with the company appeared initially in the diamond badge of 1946, when Renault was nationalised.<sup id="cite_ref-Dinesh_240-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dinesh-240">[240]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-EDM_241-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EDM-241">[241]</a></sup></p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Typeface">Typeface</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=48" title="Edit section: Typeface">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_MN">Renault MN</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=49" title="Edit section: Renault MN">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Both the Renault logo and its documentation (technical as well as commercial) historically used <i>Renault MN,</i> a custom <a href="/wiki/Typeface" title="Typeface">typeface</a> developed by British firm <a href="/wiki/Wolff_Olins" title="Wolff Olins">Wolff Olins</a>. This type family is said to have been designed mainly to save costs at a time where the use of typefaces was costly.</p>
<p>A retail version of the font family was sold by URW++ as Renault.<sup id="cite_ref-246" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-246">[246]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_Identit.C3.A9">Renault Identité</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=50" title="Edit section: Renault Identité">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In 2004, French typeface designer <a href="/wiki/Jean-Fran%C3%A7ois_Porchez" class="mw-redirect" title="Jean-François Porchez">Jean-François Porchez</a> was commissioned to design a replacement. This was shown in October of that year and was called <i>Renault Identité</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-247" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-247">[247]</a></sup> The OpenType font family was developed from the Renault logotype created by Éric de Berranger.<sup id="cite_ref-248" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-248">[248]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-249" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-249">[249]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Helvetica">Helvetica</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=51" title="Edit section: Helvetica">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Since 2007, as part of the Saguez &amp; Partners revamp, all graphic advertising makes use of <a href="/wiki/Helvetica_Neue" class="mw-redirect" title="Helvetica Neue">Helvetica Neue</a> Condensed.<sup id="cite_ref-250" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-250">[250]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg/250px-L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg" width="250" height="167" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg/375px-L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg/500px-L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3872" data-file-height="2592" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:L%27Atelier_Renault.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
L'Atelier Renault in Paris, a cultural place, gastronomy restaurant and cars showroom<sup id="cite_ref-251" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-251">[251]</a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_Life">Renault Life</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=52" title="Edit section: Renault Life">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>The Renault Life font family was built by Fontsmith Limited, based on the foundry's FS Hackney font family.<sup id="cite_ref-252" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-252">[252]</a></sup></p>
<p>The family consists of 6 fonts in 3 weights (Life, Regular, Bold) and 1 width, with complimentary italic.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="L.27Atelier_Renault_Paris">L'Atelier Renault Paris</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=53" title="Edit section: L'Atelier Renault Paris">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renault's flagship showroom, L'Atelier Renault (<small>French pronunciation:&#160;​</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_French" title="Help:IPA for French">[latəlje ʁəno]</a></span>), is located on the <a href="/wiki/Champs-%C3%89lys%C3%A9es" title="Champs-Élysées">Champs-Élysées</a> in Paris, with other manufacturers such as Peugeot, Citroën and Toyota. It opened in November 2000, located on the site of Pub Renault, which operated from 1963 to 1999. The first Renault venue at the location was the <i>Magasin Renault</i> in 1910, a pioneering car showroom.<sup id="cite_ref-253" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-253">[253]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-254" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-254">[254]</a></sup></p>
<p>L'Atelier features a Renault Boutique as well as regular exhibitions featuring Renault and Dacia cars. An upmarket restaurant is located on the second floor, looking out onto the Champs-Élysées. The ground floor can hold up to five exhibitions at any one time. As of March 2009, 20 million visitors had visited L'Atelier Renault.<sup id="cite_ref-255" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-255">[255]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-256" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-256">[256]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-257" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-257">[257]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Renault_Classic">Renault Classic</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=54" title="Edit section: Renault Classic">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Renault_Classic" title="Renault Classic">Renault Classic</a></div>
<p>Renault Classic is a department within Renault that seeks to collect, preserve and exhibit notable vehicles from the company's history. Originally named Histoire &amp; Collection, the collection was assembled in 2002 and its workshops formally opened on 24 April 2003.<sup id="cite_ref-Smith2008_258-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Smith2008-258">[258]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Music">Music</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=55" title="Edit section: Music">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, Renault's European advertising made extensive use of <a href="/wiki/Robert_Palmer_(singer)" title="Robert Palmer (singer)">Robert Palmer</a>'s song "<a href="/wiki/Johnny_and_Mary" title="Johnny and Mary">Johnny and Mary</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-259" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-259">[259]</a></sup> Television advertisements initially used Palmer's original version, while a range of special recordings in different styles were produced during the 1990s, most famously the acoustic interpretation by <a href="/wiki/Martin_Taylor_(guitarist)" title="Martin Taylor (guitarist)">Martin Taylor</a> that he released on his album <i>Spirit of Django</i>.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sponsorship">Sponsorship</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=56" title="Edit section: Sponsorship">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Renault is a sponsor of the <a href="/wiki/Port_Adelaide_Football_Club" title="Port Adelaide Football Club">Port Adelaide Football Club</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Australian_Football_League" title="Australian Football League">Australian Football League</a>, signing a three-year deal in 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-260" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-260">[260]</a></sup></p>
<p>Renault has sponsored films as an advertising technique since 1899. A Renault Voiturette Type A, driven by Louis Renault, appeared in one of the <a href="/wiki/Auguste_and_Louis_Lumi%C3%A8re" title="Auguste and Louis Lumière">Lumiéres</a>' early films.<sup id="cite_ref-261" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-261">[261]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-COLCIN_262-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-COLCIN-262">[262]</a></sup> Between 1914 and 1940, the company commissioned a series of documentary films to promote its industrial activities.<sup id="cite_ref-263" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-263">[263]</a></sup> Renault also backed some films set in Africa during the 1920s to promote the reliability of its products on tough conditions.<sup id="cite_ref-COLCIN_262-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-COLCIN-262">[262]</a></sup> Since 1983, the company sponsors the <a href="/wiki/Cannes_Film_Festival" title="Cannes Film Festival">Cannes Film Festival</a><sup id="cite_ref-264" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-264">[264]</a></sup> and it has also sponsored other festivals as the <a href="/wiki/Venice_Film_Festival" title="Venice Film Festival">Venice Film Festival</a>, the Marrakech Film Festival<sup id="cite_ref-265" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-265">[265]</a></sup> and the <a href="/wiki/BFI_London_Film_Festival" title="BFI London Film Festival">BFI London Film Festival</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-266" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-266">[266]</a></sup></p>
<p>Through its foundations and institutes, Renault funds projects around the world that focus on: education through scholarships,<sup id="cite_ref-267" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-267">[267]</a></sup> road safety and <sup id="cite_ref-268" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-268">[268]</a></sup> diversity.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Renault&amp;action=edit&amp;section=57" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

<li id="cite_note-Berliet_Renault-47"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Berliet_Renault_47-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Ager, D. E; Wright, Sue; Hantrais, Linda; Howorth, Jolyon (1974). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/?id=TlN0QLK4LhUC&amp;pg=PA47&amp;dq=louis+renault#v=onepage&amp;q=louis%20renault&amp;f=false"><i>Language, politics, and society, p. 46-47</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-85359-487-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-85359-487-8">978-1-85359-487-8</a>. <q>The activities of Louis Renault led to the spectacular expropriation of his company by the State; what is less well known is that he died in prison awaiting trial, and therefore was never convicted. The car manufacturer Marius Berliet suffered the same fate of expropriation. At his trial in September 1945, Berliet claimed in his defence that his company had produced few cars for the German occupants than any other car producer: 2239 cars for the Germans vs. 6548 for French customers. This compared to Renault which had delivered 32,887 vehicles to the Germans and only 1697 to French clients, a pattern followed by Citroen (32,248 produced for Germans and only 2052 for French clients)(Aron, 1974). Managers at Renault claimed for their part, that they had deliberately slowed down production, producing 7677 fewer vehicles than the target of 41,909 vehicles imposed by the German occupants. The argument, however, cut no ice with the Confederation Generale du Travail (CVT), who maintained that the go-slow had been organised by the workers, not the management. Louis Renault may have been punished more for his attitudes than his actions, which were mirrored by those of many other employers. Robert Aron reports that when a Gaullist seeking his support for the Free French, Renault is alleged to have replied "De Gaulle connais pas!" (Aron, 1974, 234).</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARenault&amp;rft.au=Ager%2C+D.+E&amp;rft.au=Hantrais%2C+Linda&amp;rft.au=Howorth%2C+Jolyon&amp;rft.au=Wright%2C+Sue&amp;rft.btitle=Language%2C+politics%2C+and+society%2C+p.+46-47&amp;rft.date=1974&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3DTlN0QLK4LhUC%26pg%3DPA47%26dq%3Dlouis%2Brenault%23v%3Donepage%26q%3Dlouis%2520renault%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-85359-487-8&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-48"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Auto Plus (Auto Bild France) n°1362, 10 to 17 of october 2014–1964&#160;: La Renault 8 Gordini, la première "GTi" (translation&#160;: "1964&#160;: Renault 8 Gordini, the first 'GTi'").</span></li>
